<HEADLINE> World Cycling Union defends decision to reduce doping bans f </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The International Cycling
Union vowed to continue the fight against doping in the sport
after softening penalties against three riders who admitted
taking banned substances.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Maastricht, the Netherlands, the
president of the Union Hein Verbruggen said: "For these riders,
90 percent of the season is the Tour de France."
</P>
<P>
The Union cut a month off eight-month bans handed to the
riders by the Swiss cycling federation.
</P>
<P>
The cyclists, Alex Zuelle, Laurent Dufaux and Armin Meier, all
members of the Festina Team that was ejected from the Tour
because of its systematic doping policy, will now be back in
action May 1, 1999 _ in time to prepare for next year's Tour.
</P>
<P>
At the UCI's first international congress since doping
scandals rocked the 1998 Tour de France, Verbruggen told
delegates cycling was still hurting.
</P>
<P>
"No doubt a sport like ours which depends so much on
sponsoring money must feel the negative ramifications from what
happened," he was quoted as saying. "I know that _ we all know
that _ and we have to fight to make things better."
</P>
<P>
The UCI stepped up the battle by forming an anti-doping work
group, funded by national federations, cycling teams and riders.
</P>
<P>
The group, which includes representatives of the UCI, riders
and professional teams, will consider ways of fighting the
acknowledged widespread drug abuse among cyclists.  
</P>
</TEXT>
