<HEADLINE> Russia Against Use of Force in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Russia opposes any use of force
in the Kosovo crisis, especially without U.N. Security Council
approval, the Russian Foreign Ministry said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Unless urgent steps are taken to remedy the situation in
Kosovo, NATO may go ahead with its plans to use force against
Yugoslavia," said ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov, Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev
and First Deputy Foreign Intelligence Service Director Alexei
Scherbakov, who visited Yugoslavia on Sunday, gave a message from
President Boris Yeltsin to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic,
which warned that NATO may use force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that NATO strikes would be avoided only if
the Yugoslavian army and security units were withdrawn to
barracks, urgent steps taken to resolve the humanitarian crisis
and allow the refugees to return their homes, and impetus given to
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
These steps, vigorously supported by the United Nations and
other international organizations, would lead to a political
solution to the Kosovo crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he noted that these demands also apply to the
political leaders of Kosovo ethnic Albanians, who must take steps
to end terrorist activities and unambiguously dissociate
themselves from separatist plans.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic expressed thanks to Yeltsin for his efforts in
resolving the crisis and said that Belgrade would do its best to
implement the understandings reached between Milosevic and Yeltsin
on June 16, 1998, and the U.N. provisions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
