<HEADLINE> EU Appeals for Bi-Communal Cypriot Accession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Union said on
Monday that its objective to grant Cyprus a full membership
remains a bi-communal, bi-zonal federation on the island state.
</P>
<P>
The European Union foreign ministers, meeting in their general
affairs council, regretted the fact that it had not been possible
to find a political solution to the continuing division of Cyprus
in time for the accession negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The analytical examination by the European Commission could not
cover Cyprus as a whole and the invitation of the Cyprus
government to include representatives of the Turkish Cypriot
community in the accession negotiations had so far not been taken
up.
</P>
<P>
The European Union believed, said Greek Foreign Minister
Theodoros Pangalos, that Cyprus' accession to the union should
benefit all communities and help to bring about civil peace and
reconciliation on the island.
</P>
<P>
A political settlement in accordance with United Nations
resolutions would allow the provisions of the accession treaty to
be implemented throughout the island, and progress toward
accession and toward a just and viable solution to the Cyprus
problem will naturally reinforce each other, he added.
</P>
<P>
The European Union pledged its full support for the search of a
solution for Cyprus under the aegis of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
In December last year, the European Union invited Cyprus as
well as Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic, Slovenia and Estonia
to start accession talks.
</P>
<P>
The move angered Turkey, a long-time applicant for EU
membership.
</P>
<P>
Turkey thereafter refused an invitation to attend the inaugural
pan-European Conference held this March in London and may still be
absent from Tuesday's second pan-European Conference at foreign
minister level in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
The EU foreign ministers agreed on Monday that starting from
November 10, the accession negotiations will be upgraded to
ministerial level with real substances.
</P>
<P>
Seven of the 11 sets of accession requirements will be
discussed in detail in the November negotiations, according to
Monday's foreign minister council.
</P>
<P>
The Greek foreign minister, however, did not completely rule
out the possibility of granting membership to
partilly-represented Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
