<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cook Says Britain Ready to Use Force in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook said here Monday Britain was ready to use force in a possible
NATO intervention in Kosovo, Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a special meeting of the British defense
committee early Monday, Cook told reporters that the Yugoslav
government had to obey a U.N. Security Council resolution
demanding the cease of all violence in Kosovo, where some 30
ethnic Albanians have been killed over the past week.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want to use force but if force is the only measure
(Yugoslav) President Milosevic is going to listen to, Britain is
ready to back force," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Cook noted that Britain has confirmed that "we are united in
our resolve that President (Slobodan) Milosevic must be compelled
to change his behavior in Kosovo and to abide by the terms of the
Security Council resolution."
</P>
<P>
"Britain will now be using this week to build the same unity
and resolve among the wider international community. Milosevic has
only a few days this week to listen to what the international
community is saying to him," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Early Sunday, British Defense Secretary George Robertson
dropped a a hint that NATO may send troops to Kosovo to enforce a
possible ceasefire.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
