<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin, Annan Have Phone Talks on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris
Yeltsin on Monday morning called U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, and they talked for 25 minutes on "the critical situation"
in Kosovo, Serbia's province of mainly ethnic Albanians, a U.N.
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Fred Eckhard, spokesman for the U.N. chief, told a press
conference that Yeltsin, during the phone conversation, briefed
Annan on "the efforts his government was making to ensure
President (Solobodan) Milosevic and the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia to fully comply with the U.n. Security Council
resolution 1199.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council adopted the resolution on September 23,
calling for an immediate ceasefire in Kosovo and an entry to
political talks.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman declined to give more details on the
Yeltsin-Annan phone talks.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Foreign Ministry said in Moscow on Monday that
Russia opposes any use of force in the Kosovo crisis, especially
without approval from the 15-member Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov, Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev and First Deputy Foreign Intelligence Service Director
Alexei Scherbakov, who visited Yugoslavia on Sunday, gave a
message from Yeltsin to Milosevic, which warned the NATO may use
force in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
