<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Stands for Dialogue on Human Rights, Qin Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Qin made the statement after he signed the International
Covenant on Civil and Political Rights on behalf of the Chinese
Government.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, China has concluded dialogue and exchanges
with some countries in the field of human rights, he said, adding
that practice has proved that this is very useful for the
enhancement fo mutual understanding and enlargement of common
ground.
</P>
<P>
"As a Member State of the United Nations, China has always
actively participated in the activities of the organization in the
field of human rights," he said, "It attaches importance to its
cooperation with agencies concerned in the U.N. system."
</P>
<P>
"Not long ago, Ms. (Mary) Robinson, the United Nations High
Commissioner for Human Rights had just paid a successful visit to
China," he said, "Her visit has helped both sides understand each
other better."
</P>
<P>
China values the role of international human rights instruments
in promoting and protecting human rights, he said, adding that his
country has acceded to 17 international human rights covenants.
</P>
<P>
In October last year, the Chinese Government signed the
International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights. At
present, the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress
of China, the Chinese parliament, is deliberating on the
ratification of the Covenant, he said.
</P>
<P>
"All these have demonstrated the firm resolve of China to
promote and protect human rights," he said, "They are also China's
concrete deeds to honor the 50th anniversary of the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights and the 5th anniversary of the Vienna
Declaration of Programme of Action."
</P>
<P>
"I would like to reaffirm here the willingness of the Chinese
Government to further its cooperation with U.N. in the field of
human rights in an effort to push forward together the
development of the international cause of human rights," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Covenant was adopted by the General Assembly and opened
for signature in 1966. Together with the International Covenant
on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights, both Covenants entered
into force in 1976.  
</P>
</TEXT>
