<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Urges Syria, Turkey to Ease Tensions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia on Monday urged
Syria and Turkey to resolve their disputes through diplomatic
means in a bid to avert a possible armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
Riyadh hopes that Turkey "as a friendly Islamic country will
continue the dialogue with Syria to resolve the disputes with
peaceful means," Saudi Information Undersecretary Madani Alaki
told reporters after a cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Saudi Arabia views Syria and Turkey as two neighboring states
bound with substantial interests," Alaki said, quoted by the Saudi
Press Agency.
</P>
<P>
Tensions are mounting between Syria and Turkey after they
traded accusations against each other, and Turkey has reportedly
massed troops along its border with Syria.
</P>
<P>
The two neighbors have long been at odds over issues including
Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), water sharing and
the Turkish-Israeli military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has accused Syria of harboring the PKK, which has been
fighting since 1984 for an independent Kurdish state in the
southeast of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Syria has lashed out at Turkey, a predominantly Muslim country,
for forming a military alliance with Israel, which it says is
targeted against the Arab world, especially itself, and undermines
its bargaining position in negotiations with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Syria has disputes with Israel over the future of the Golan
Heights, captured by Israel in the 1967 Middle East War. Damascus
insisted on its return as a condition for peace with the Jewish
state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
