<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak's Visit to Ankara Aims at Containing Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 5 (Xinhua) -- President Hosni Mubarak's visit
Tuesday to Turkey envisions containing the current crisis and
building a dialog system between Ankara and Damascus, Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on the eve of Mubarak's high-profile
visit to Turkey, Moussa said the Syrian-Turkish question is
complicated but it is not impossible to solve through diplomacy
instead of military escalation.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt looks to Syria as a sisterly Arab country and to Turkey
as a friendly Islamic country," Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
"Talks between President Mubarak and his Turkish counterpart
Suleyman Demirel will focus just on the Syrian-Turkish crisis. We
hope that Egypt's good offices would succeed in defusing the
crisis," he added.
</P>
<P>
Moussa declined to reveal details about the proposals Mubarak
will be carrying to Ankara. He pointed out, however, that the
recent Syrian statement calls for dialog with Turkey to solve the
pending problems between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, who held talks with Syrian President Hafez al-Assad
during a whirlwind trip to Damascus Sunday aimed at heading off a
military confrontation, has called on both sides to restrain from
any provocative actions.
</P>
<P>
"President Mubarak will go to Turkey as representative of the
Arab side and chairman of the Arab summit that calls for peace in
the region," he added.
</P>
<P>
Asked if Egypt is intervening to partially solve the problem or
take it by the root, Moussa chose the second option and added that
Egypt is seeking to establish a positive relationship between the
two neighbor countries.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is endeavoring to set up a "mechanism for dialogue"
between Ankara and Damascus, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Strained ties between Syria and Turkey deteriorated in recent
weeks. Turkey accused Syria of aiding Kurdish rebels fighting for
autonomy in southeast Turkey, while Syria bridled at Turkey's
growing military links with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Turkey said on Saturday that it plans a military exercise along
the Syrian border after the end of the current exercises of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization in the area.
</P>
<P>
It also announced fresh naval maneuvers in the eastern
Mediterranean and joint air exercises, which Syria says are
directed against itself. 
</P>
</TEXT>
