<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Says No Concession over Missile Deployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Defense Minister
Yiannakis Omirou said on Monday that Cyprus will go ahead with the
plan to deploy Russian-made anti-aircraft missiles and not make
any concessions over the issue.
</P>
<P>
"No concessions will be made regarding the Cyprus Republic's
sovereign right to proceed with the necessary armaments to boost
its defense," Omirou said on the sidelines of a meeting in Athens
on cooperation with Greece in the arms industry, the Cyprus News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on reports that the deployment of the
missiles would be delayed for a second time until the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot official blamed the reports for creating "a danger
of diverting the attention of the world public opinion from the
Cyprus problem, which needs to be solved in accordance with
international law."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus ordered the S-300 missiles last year in a bid to boost
its air defense. The move was opposed by Turkish Cypriots and
Turkey, which has threatened to take pre-emptive measures if they
are deployed.
</P>
<P>
Under pressures from the United States and Britain, which were
also against the missile plan, Cypriot government has decided to
postpone the delivery of the missiles from August till November.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey maintains more than 35,000 troops in northern Cyprus to
allegedly protect the Turkish Cypriot minority, who declared
unilaterally in 1983 a breakaway state recognized only by Ankara.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
