<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Discusses Kosovo with German, U.N. and </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
on Monday evening had a telephone conversation with German
chancellor-elect Gerhard Schroeder on situation in Kosovo,
according to the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin told Schroeder that Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic had accepted his proposals, including to invite an
mission of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
(OSCE) to Kosovo, that the Yugoslav parliament and government had
decided to invite a OSCE mission to the warring region.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder appreciated Yeltsin's efforts to ensure a negotiated
settlement in Kosovo and expressed hope that they will yield
positive results.
</P>
<P>
Both leaders were satisfied with the establishment of regular
contacts even before a new German government has been formed, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The Russian president afterward had a long and substantive
conversation with U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan to discuss the
Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Annan favored Russia's efforts to resolve the crisis which are
consonant with the U.N. stance and hoped that they will help
stabilize the situation in Kosovo by political means, the Russian
presidential press service said.
</P>
<P>
Annan stressed the need for Belgrade to take concrete measures
to stop violence, create conditions for the return of refugees and
promote cooperation with international humanitarian organizations.
</P>
<P>
On Monday evening, Yeltsin also discussed Kosovo situation with
U.S. President Bill Clinton by a telephone call.
</P>
<P>
According to the press service, Clinton spoke favorably of
Russia's efforts and voiced hope that the Yugoslav leadership,
being aware of the whole seriousness of the situation, will adopt
effective measures to correct the situation in Kosovo and start
practical cooperation with OSCE and other world bodies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
