<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM for Riyadh over Syria-Turkey Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri Monday night left here for Riyadh to discuss with Saudi
leaders the mounting tensions between Syrian and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Orient Radio here said reported that during his two-day
stay, Hariri will hold talks with Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz
and senior officials on the issue and other regional affairs.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure, Harir said in an interview with Lebanese
daily An Nahar that Lebanon stands by Syria, especially in its
calls for resolving disputes with Turkey through peaceful dialog.
</P>
<P>
"We are worried by the Turkish threats and military buildup
and hope that (Egyptian) President (Hosni) Mubarak's endeavor
would defuse the current combustion," he added.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to ease tension that many fear could spill over
to the entire region, Mubarak made a trouble-shooting mission
which has taken him to Saudi Arabia and Syria.
</P>
<P>
The often tense relations between Turkey and Syria have
deteriorated in recent weeks as they traded accusations. Turkey
alleged that Syria harbors its Kurdish rebels, which Damascus
denied.
</P>
<P>
Syria was worried about Turkey's growing military alliance with
Israel that threats Arab security, and its building of a string of
dams on the Euphrates River, which could reduce Syria's already
short supply of water.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Turkey has massed some 10,000 troops along the
Syrian border, and threatened to resort to military means if
Damascus continued to aid the Kurdish rebels.
</P>
<P>
Hariri said that Turkey's threats are the products of the
newly-concluded Turkish-Israeli strategic pact. Turkish Prime
Minister Mesut Yilmaz has recently concluded an official visit to
Israel in which the two countries agreed to expand military
cooperation, including holding a joint military maneuver.
</P>
<P>
The move was described by Arab countries, especially Syria, as
the formal launch of a military alliance between Israel and Turkey
aimed at encircling them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
