<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gypsies' Situation in Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, October 5 (Xinhua) -- As many as 59 percent of Gypsy
women living in Romania and 44 percent of their male counterparts
are illiterate, a specialist study commissioned by the Romanian
Ministry of Education showed on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Only a meagre 4.5 percent of the whole community are high
school graduates. Of the total number of 7-to-10-year-olds, only
half of them are regular school goers. 40 percent of the under-8s
do not attend either kindergarten or school and 7 percent of them
do not have birth certificates, the study said.
</P>
<P>
Romania is currently the most heavily-Gypsy inhabited European
country, and the Gypsy community here, also known as Rroma, is the
youngest and most boosting in terms of births. Members of the
community are commonly seen as inadaptable, self-exclusive and
hard to integrate with the wider community.
</P>
<P>
Official figures at the last 1992 population census in Romania
put the Gypsy community at 409,723, that is 1.8 percent of the
whole population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
