<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia-Pacific PC Market Down Slightly in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, October 5 (Xinhua) -- China and Australia have
become increasingly important to the growth of the Asia-Pacific
region as PC vendors struggle to remain buoyant in this part of
the world, a U.S. market analysis firm said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The two countries contributed 37 percent and 25 percent
respectiively of the total PC shipments in the region in the
second quarter this year, according to the California-based
Dataquest. Shipments in China came to almost 810,000 units between
April and June, up 48 percent from the quarter a year ago, while
Australia's shipments totaled 549,000 units.
</P>
<P>
As a whole, Dataquest said in a report, the region's PC
shipments in the second quarter of 1998 declined 0.2 percent from
the quarter a year ago. Overall shipments in the 10 major markets
in the region totaled 2.2 million units.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, Indonesia, South Korea and Malaysia posted the
largest declines in the quarter. However, there were some positive
signs in Thailand, as the quarter revealed the first
quarter-to-quarter growth in shipments at about two percent since
the economic crisis began.
</P>
<P>
The industry in Hong Kong has slowed down, with a growth of
less than one percent in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
Singapore and Taiwan are the latest casualties in the Asian
crisis, Dataquest said. In Singapore, the industry posted its
first negative year-to-year results, with a decline of 18 percent
in unit shipments. PC shipments in Taiwan registered a decline of
three percent.
</P>
<P>
India posted a year-to-year growth of 25 percent, with a
shipment of 133,000 units in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
"The performance of the second half of the year will be
dependent on the success of the reforms of the government to
stabilize the market," said the Dataquest report, referring to the
Asia-Pacific region's PC market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
