<HEADLINE> Kenyan Teachers Start Strike, Clash with Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Tens of thousands of teachers
in support of the teachers.
Some 500 students blocked a main road 30 kilometers west of
Nairobi with fires, stoning passing motorists and the police. The
latter responded with tear-gas and rubber bullets.
</P>
<P>
In Migori District, southwestern Kenya, scores of teachers
were injured and one policeman was badly beaten in violent
clashes, Kenya News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The strike by teachers at public schools also affected the
operation of private schools. Sources told Xinhua that more than
half of the pupils were absent at Nairobi's private schools which
had canceled all scheduled extra curricula due to the strike.
</P>
<P>
Striking teachers demonstrated outside private schools,
causing disturbances among the pupils there. Local analysts
predicted that the situation will be tenser in the coming couple
of days.
</P>
<P>
In the Braeburn Primary School, one of the leading private
schools in Nairobi, the teachers have asked parents to take their
children in and out of school themselves instead of using school
commuters.
</P>
<P>
Labor Minister Joseph Ngutu charged in a statement Monday that
the striking teachers were in breach of a no-strike agreement,
warning that they "must take full responsibility for their
actions."
