<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developed Nations Urged to Increase ODA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- China on Monday called on
developed countries to live up to their obligations in official
development assistance (ODA) as its decline worries developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
The ODA has dropped to an all-time low, taking up only 0.22
percent of the gross national product (GDP) of developed countries
and a mere 0.19 percent of that of the seven most developed ones,
said Shen Guofang, China's Deputy Permanent Representative to the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
China hopes that developed countries will "reach the agreed
targets on the issue of voluntary contribution as soon as
possible," Sheng told the General Assembly which was debating on
the annual report of Secretary-General Kofi Annan on the work of
the U.N..
</P>
<P>
He said the world body continued to play an active role in
maintaining world peace and security during the past year.
</P>
<P>
The organization has paid much attention to exploring and
wiping out the root cause of the conflicts, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council held two meetings at the level of foreign
ministers on the causes of the conflicts and the promotion of
lasting peace and sustainable development in Africa, he added.
</P>
<P>
Shen suggested that the U.N. work even harder to solve the
problems facing developing countries, especially in the fields of
boosting investment and growth, dealing with the challenges of
globalization, making necessary readjustment and avoiding the
breakout of economic and social crisis. 
</P>
