<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan: I Have No Means to Verify Yugoslav Compliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Monday blamed Yugoslav forces for most of the
atrocities in the Serb province of Kosovo and said that he didn't
have the means to verify whether Belgrade had complied with the
Security Council demanding an end to hostilities.
</P>
<P>
In a written report to the 15-member Security Council, Annan,
who decried the "appalling atrocities in Kosovo," said that the
Kosovar Albanians have also engaged in armed action.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear beyond any reasonable doubt that the great
majority of such acts have been committed by security forces in
Kosovo acting under the authority of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia (FRY)," he said, "But Kosovar Albanian paramilitary
units have engaged in armed action also, and there is good reason
to believe that they too have committed atrocities."
</P>
<P>
Annan said that, unlike situation where the United Nations had
a presence on the ground, he did not "have the means necessary to
provide an independent assessment of compliance" with the Security
Council resolution by the FRY.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, the Council may wish to make its own judgement in
this respect on the basis of the present report," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution adopted on September 23, the Security Council
demanded a ceasefire, the withdrawal of special forces from
Kosovo and a negotiated settlement.
</P>
<P>
In his widely anticipated report, the U.N. chief said that in
the week following the September 23 resolution, the Yugoslav
government forces "intensified their operations, launching another
offensive in the Drenica region" and other areas.
</P>
<P>
As a result, another 20,000 people were displaced, he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is a need for a thorough investigation, under
effective international control or with international
participation, of all reported cases of atrocities and
violations of human rights," he said.
</P>
<P>
Serbia is the larger of the two republics comprising the FRY.
Ethnic Albanians, who form a majority of Kosovo's population of
2 million, have been battling Serbs for independence.
</P>
<P>
Annan's report came as NATO forces prepared for possible
military intervention in Kosovo, which has been seen as an
internal affair by Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
He said that conditions must be created to allow the return of
a significant number of displaced persons, including a "radical
change of policy and behavior and the introduction of
confidence-building measures -- such as withdrawal of police
units, a declaration of amnesty of and a release of
prisoners."  
</P>
</TEXT>
