<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Parties Agree to Consider SADC Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Rival Lesotho political
parties Monday agreed to consider a Southern African Development
Community (SADC) proposal for setting up a transitional structure
to ensure free and fair elections in the mountain kingdom.
</P>
<P>
"We will take it to the people... and if they say yes to it,
we will also say yes," South African Press Association (SAPA)
quoted opposition alliance spokesman Vincent Malebo as saying in
Maseru.
</P>
<P>
He said if they did not get a mandate from their supporters,
they would resort to other ways of overcoming the political
impasse.
</P>
<P>
Deputy chief of the ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy
(LCD), Kelebone Maope, said his party did not in principle have
problems with the proposal.
</P>
<P>
He said he was pleased that his party would continue to rule
until the election takes place in 15 to 18 months time.
</P>
<P>
SADC presented the proposal to the Lesotho government and
opposition parties at Monday's talks after the two sides
disagreed on who should govern the country before fresh elections
in 15 to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
The government said it was legitimately elected and should
remain in power, while opposition parties insisted a government
of national unity should be formed.
</P>
<P>
The SADC proposal suggested that while the present government
would continue to rule the country, the structure should prepare
the nation for the elections.
</P>
<P>
The structure would consist of one or two members from each of
the political parties, announced South African safety and
security minister, Sydney Mufamadi, who chaired Monday's meeting
of the Lesotho government and opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
The structure would ensure equitable treatment of all
political parties by state-owned broadcasting and information
services in the period leading up to the elections.
</P>
<P>
It would have the power to access all information held by
government relevant to the elections and the power to adopt and
enforce a code of conduct for all political parties.
</P>
<P>
It would take decisions on all electoral matters including the
role of the police, military services, intelligence services,
foreign affairs, media and publications, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The structure would also appoint a new independent electoral
commission to review Lesotho's electoral system, with a view to
empowering to perform its functions.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on fresh elections was reached by government and
opposition parties on Friday after an military intervention of
the political crisis resulted in bloody conflict between mutinous
Lesotho soldiers and South African and Botswanan troops.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties claim that the May 23 general election was
rigged in favor of the LCD, which won 79 of 80 seats in the
National Assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
