<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Debating Impeachment Inquiry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 5 (Xinhua) - The U.S. House of
Representatives Judiciary Committee Monday opened a debate on
whether to launch a formal impeachment inquiry against President
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The committee, where Republicans have a 21-16 majority, was
expected to vote later in the day or on Tuesday to conduct an
open-ended, unrestricted investigation of the president and his
affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
"We are not here today to decide whether or not to impeach Mr.
Clinton. We are not here to pass judgment on anyone," committee
chairman Henry Hyde, an Illinois Republican, said in opening the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
"We are here to ask and answer this one single question --
based on what we now know -- do we have a duty to look further or
to look away?" Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
Chief Republican investigator David Schippers told the
committee he believed Clinton had committed 15 potentially
impeachable acts, four more than independent counsel Kenneth Starr
had alleged in his report to Congress last month.
</P>
<P>
He split some counts and added others involving conspiracy and
aiding the filing of a false affidavit, but dropped abuse of power
charges stemming from White House privilege claims and Clinton's
refusal to voluntarily testify.
</P>
<P>
Democratic chief investigator Abbe Lowell said Schippers was
adding charges by "subdividing" the existing facts and citing a
"laundry list of laws" Clinton might have violated.
</P>
<P>
The Judiciary Committee has a reputation as one of the most
partisan groups in Congress.
</P>
<P>
Republicans said it was their constitutional duty to pursue the
allegations forwarded to Congress by Starr, while Democrats
questioned if the charges amounted to the "high crimes and
misdemeanors" spelled out in the Constitution as a basis for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
"This is not Watergate, it is an extramarital affair," said
Representative John Conyers of Michigan, the ranking Democrat on
the committee.
</P>
<P>
Both sides warned that partisanship could destroy the process
and ruin what remains of Congress' reputation.
</P>
<P>
The Republican resolution of inquiry would not set a deadline
for ending the investigation and would allow it to move beyond the
Lewinsky matter to such issues as Whitewater, campaign finance
abuses or the White House travel office firings.
</P>
<P>
Democrats will offer an alternative resolution limiting the
probe to the Lewinsky matter and forcing it to end by Thanksgiving
on Nov. 26.
</P>
<P>
Once approved by the committee the resolution of inquiry would
have to be voted on by the full 435-member House.
</P>
<P>
Polls have shown the public continues to give Clinton high
marks as president even though they disapprove of his affair with
Lewinsky. The majority of polls have shown many Americans would
like to see an end to the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
A CBS News poll released on Monday showed that by a margin of
56 to 38 percent, respondents said the committee should not begin
an impeachment inquiry and disapproved of the way the panel was
doing its job by a 53 to 34 percent margin. The poll, which
sampled 902 adults on Saturday and Sunday, had a margin of error
of three percentage points.
</P>
<P>
Hyde acknowledged the public was getting tired but said
Congress still had to perform its constitutional duty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Yeltsin Talk About Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Monday told Russian President Boris Yeltsin by phone of U.S.
concern that Yugoslavia was making "false" promises to stall
military strikes by the West.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the latest Serb troop movements in Kosovo, White
House spokesman Joe Lockhart said that Clinton stressed the idea
that "we've been down this road before and that only full
compliance" would prevent allied strikes in the province.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, who opposes NATO plans to use air strikes to halt the
violence in Kosovo, spoke with Clinton about the efforts of a
high-level ministerial delegation he sent to Belgrade during the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said Clinton told the Russian leader "he was concerned
that Milosevic was playing the classic game of making false
promises designed to remove international pressure.
</P>
<P>
"He made the point that we don't wish to use force but what
happens next depends upon President Milosevic," Lockhart told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke was in Belgrade Monday to
warn the Yugoslav president that air strikes were inevitable
unless U.N. demands were met.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Serb movements, State Department spokesman
James Rubin said that the United States sees clear signs that Serb
troops are pulling back in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. plans to maintain a threat of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) force against Yugoslavia until the
withdrawal is irreversible and peace talks are launched.
</P>
<P>
"But what we're looking for is that this is a comprehensive
pullback and that it's not reversible.... This can't be just a
temporary step," Rubin told reporters flying with Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Albright spoke to European allies by telephone Sunday and is
likely to visit NATO headquarters later this week as the alliance
moves towards a decision on launching air strikes to end Serb
attacks on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In her conversation with the foreign ministers of Italy,
Britain, France, Austria and Russia, Albright argued that "it is
only the credible threat of the use of force... that will ensure a
genuine strategic change by (President Slobodan) Milosevic," Rubin
said. 
</P>
