<HEADLINE> Turkey Softens Tone over Tension with Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- As most Arab countries urged
Turkey and Syria to exercise self-restraint and solve their crisis
through diplomatic means, Turkey softened its tone on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Air Force Commander Ilhan Kilic said in the
southeastern city of Diyarbakir that Turkey is a supporter of
peace, and believes bilateral disputes can be solved through
crisis management.
</P>
<P>
"If the problem is not solved through diplomacy, other methods
will follow, but the nation does not want war," he said.
</P>
<P>
Military Academies Commander Necati Ozgen said here that war
is not desired, and "we will make efforts to reach our national
goals through diplomacy, crisis management or deterrence."
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz, Foreign Minister Ismail Cem and
other high-ranking officials discussed the latest developments of
the on-going tensions with Syria at a meeting, which lasted one
hour and a half. But no details were available.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President Suleyman Demirel talked on telephone with
Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan on ways to ease the tensions between
Ankara and Damascus.
</P>
<P>
On Monday evening, Demirel met with Cem to discuss the
situation, which threatened to escalate to a military
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
But the essence of the crisis seemed to have united Arab states
against Turkey. Demirel has accused Syria of trying to provoke
the Arab world against Ankara by using Turkey's close ties with
Israel as a pretext.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, a predominantly Muslim but politically secular country,
has been attacked by Arab countries for forming a military
alliance with Israel, which is regarded as a threat to Arab
security.
</P>
<P>
Syria, for one, said the Turkish-Israeli alliance is targeted
against the Arab world, especially itself, and accused Turkey of
betraying the interests of the Muslims.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Turkey accused Syria of harboring its
Kurdish rebels, who have been waging a 14-year-old armed campaign
on for independence in southeast Turkey. But Syria denied the
charge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
