<HEADLINE> Iran Reiterates Demand to Punish Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Monday reiterated its
demands to punish the killers of Iranian nationals in Afghanistan,
return the bodies of the other three victims and release other
Iranians held by the Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
"Iran's demands are the same of the international community
and the Taliban should submit to the international demands,"
Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi said during a meeting with United
Nations envoy on Afghanistan Lakhdar Brahimi.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi called on the world community to pressure the Taliban
into abiding by international will, particularly the U.N. Security
Council resolution 1193 urging the Afghan militia to stop
genocide, the official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban militia killed nine Iranian diplomats and a
reporter last August in northern Afghanistan. The bodies of six
diplomats and the reporter have been returned to Iran last month,
but those of the three others have not yet been found.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said that Iran is making efforts to solve the
problems with the Taliban through diplomatic means, but its
tolerance is limited.
</P>
<P>
"We hope we will not be forced to resort to other means," he
said, hinting at the military option.
</P>
<P>
Angered by Taliban's killings, Iran has massed some 270,000
troops along its border with Afghanistan and threatened
retaliation against the Taliban, which now control most of the
country.
</P>
<P>
In a separate meeting with the U.N. envoy, Iranian Defense
Minister Ali Shamkhani said the least service expected of the
international community is to arrest and bring to justice the
killers of the Iranian nationals.
</P>
<P>
Shamkhani reiterated the "full readiness" of Iranian armed
forces to defend against any crimes on the country's borders.
</P>
<P>
He voiced Tehran's readiness to offer every possible help to
the U.N. in a bid to control the current turmoil in neighboring
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi expressed appreciation of Iran's restraint over the
slaying of its nationals, saying that attacks against diplomats
should be condemned under every condition.
</P>
<P>
He underlined the need for the Taliban to release other Iranian
citizens as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban admitted that it held more than 30 Iranian drivers
and aid workers.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy arrived here on Sunday for a four-day visit.
After wrapping up his visit here, Brahimi will travel to Pakistan
to explore ways of easing the tensions between Iran and the
Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Iran is viewed as a close ally of the Afghan opposition
Northern Alliance while Pakistan is believed to have been
supporting the Taliban, which now imposes a strict version of
Islamic rule in Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says U.N. Report Shows Belgrade Defiant on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Monday a U.N. report on Kosovo showed it was "crystal clear" that
Yugoslav leaders were defying demands to end the conflict.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley also said that the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) was close to a decision on
military action, but refused to give a date.
</P>
<P>
"So our view -- preliminary view of the secretary-general's
report is that it makes crystal-clear that there has not been
compliance on the part of the Serb authorities with demands
contained in U.N. Security Council Resolution 1199," said Foley.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council Resolution demands Belgrade to stop
the fighting in Kosovo, withdraw all the Serbian forces and launch
negotiations with the ethnic Albanians who are seeking
independence of the province.
</P>
<P>
A report by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan released on
Monday on whether Belgrade complied with the resolution blamed
Serbia for most of the recent atrocities in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Foley said that Serbia should shoulder the major responsibility
although both sides have taken actions of killing civilians.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that such actions have taken place on both sides,
however, and that we condemn atrocities and killings of civilians,
no matter who perpetrates them, wherever they occur," said Foley.
</P>
<P>
"And we believe they have to be investigated thoroughly and
those guilty brought to justice," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the "overwhelming evidence indicates that the
atrocities and the killings of civilians have occurred
overwhelmingly on the Serb side."
</P>
<P>
Foley indicated the the 16-member NATO will make a decision on
military action in Kosovo soon.
</P>
<P>
"We're not far from such a decision. But that decision will
have to be taken by the political authorities of the 16 NATO
nations, based on the evidence that is in front of them at the
time they meet to decide that," he said.
</P>
<P>
"That day is not far off, unless we see what would have to be a
strategic and definitive and irreversible change on the part of
the Serb authorities' attitude and behavior," Foley told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the decision will be made by political leaders
of NATO countries.
</P>
<P>
While the alliance is threatening military actions, U.S.
special envoy Richard Holbrooke were trying in Belgrade to
persuade the Yugoslav leader to change their minds in order to
avert a confrontation in Kosovo between NATO and Serbia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
