<HEADLINE> Annan, Aziz to Meet Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan and Iraq's Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz would hold
the third round of talks at the United Nations Wednesday, U.N.
spokesman Fred Eckhard said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Annan and Aziz held two rounds of talks last week. But Iraq has
not reversed its decision to suspend cooperation with the United
Nations weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will coincide with or immediately follow a
half-year report from the United Nations Special Commission in
charge of dismantling Iraq's ballistical, chemical and biological
weapons and the Vienna-based International Atomic Energy Agency
responsible for Iraq's nuclear programs.
</P>
<P>
Aziz has been here for a week, during which he consulted with
Annan and members of the Security Council on what a new
comprehensive review of Iraq's relations with the United Nations
would contain. Aziz is not expected to make a decision on whether
to rescind Iraq's ban on most U.N. arms inspections until he
leaves New York and speaks to Iraq's President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Iraq announced suspension of cooperation with the United
Nations arms inspectors in early August. The Security Council
decided to suspend its regular review on U.N. sanctions against
Iraq until it resumes cooperation with the United Nations. The
council offered a comprehensive review of Iraq's compliance with
U.N. relevant resolutions once it resumes cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
