<HEADLINE> Turkish FM: Syria Blocks Way to Diplomacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem said Monday that Syria blocks the way to a diplomatic solution
to the disputes between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
According to local media, in the central province of Kayseri
Cem said that nothing can be an excuse for incidents of violence
and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"Every country has the right to defend herself against
terrorism, and Turkey will certainly do what is necessary, as she
has the power, experience, belief and courage to do that," he said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long accused Syria of harboring its Kurdish rebels,
who have been fighting since 1984 for an independent homeland in
southeastern Turkey. It even threatened to use force to destroy
Kurdish bases inside Syria.
</P>
<P>
Cem said Turkey continues to take necessary diplomatic
initiatives to make Syria stop giving money, weapons and logistics
support to the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
However, he said Turkey's diplomatic initiatives in the past
did not get any result, adding that this time Syria tries to
connect the Turkish position to elements like Israel in a bid to
mislead and provoke other Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, a predominantly Muslim but politically secular state,
has been attacked by most Arab countries for forming a military
alliance with Israel, which is regarded as a threat to Arab
security.
</P>
<P>
Syria denied it is sheltering Kurdish rebels, and said that the
Turkish-Israeli alliance is targeted against the Arab world,
especially itself, and betraying the interests of the Muslims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
