<HEADLINE> Lebanon Denies Harboring Kurdish Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon Monday denied there are
bases or militants of Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party
(PKK) in its territory or in Syria.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Foreign Minister Fares Boueiz told a news conference
here that Turkey's accusations about PKK's "continuing activities"
in Lebanon and Syria are "not justified."
</P>
<P>
"The Turkish authorities knows that Lebanon and Syria took
measures to stop any activities of PKK members at least one and a
half years ago," Boueiz said.
</P>
<P>
Ankara has accused Damascus of harboring PKK rebels, who have
been fighting since 1984 for an independent Kurdish state in the
southeast of Turkey. It has massed troops on its border with
Syria, threatening to destroy Kurdish bases inside Syria.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Milliyet daily said on Sunday that Turkish troops
might pinpoint targets in Lebanon's Bekaa Valley controlled by
Syrian forces. Turkey claims that PKK rebels maintain camps there.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz said that his country is studying the possibility of
calling for an Arab summit to discuss the Turkish threats which
target the Arab countries' interests.
</P>
<P>
Syria maintains 35,000 troops as peacekeepers in Lebanon. The
two countries agree to coordinate stances on key issues.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese President Elias Hrawi traveled to Damascus Monday for
talks with President Hafez al-Assad on means of defusing tension,
while Prime Minister Rafik Hariri flew to Riyadh to solicit
support from King Fahd for a diplomatic approach to the crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
