<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2120 GMT, October 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak has said that Egypt
will join the nuclear club and retaliate in kind if it is
threatened by Israel, an Arabic-language newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We do not at present think of entering the nuclear club
because we do not want war. War does not solve any difference.
Still peace needs power to protect," he said in an interview with
the mass-circulated "Al-Hayat."
</P>
<P>
"We are not in a hurry (to acquire nuclear arms)...But if the
time comes when we need the nuclear weapon, we would not
hesitate...This is the last thing on our mind," he said.
(Egypt-Israel-Nuclear Weapons)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Hundreds of Palestinians held demonstrations in
the Gaza Strip Monday, demanding the release of Palestinian
prisoners held by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that among the demonstrators were the
family members of the prisoners and the supporters of the Islamic
militant group Hamas.
</P>
<P>
Sheik Ahmed Yassin, the spiritual leader of Hamas, also
attended the rally, but did not address the crowd.
(Palestine-Demonstration)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Palestinians hope that U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright will compel the Israeli side to remain within
the limits of signed agreements and implement them.
</P>
<P>
This was made clear by Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb
Erekat on Monday in the West Bank town of Jericho in an interview
with the Voice of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said the Palestinian side also wants Albright to obtain
political decisions from Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
to reach agreements on issues being discussed by the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Albright is scheduled to arrive here on Tuesday to push
forward the peace process and to prepare for a tripartite meeting
due to take place in Washington by mid-October among Netanyahu,
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, and U.S. President Bill Clinton.
(Israel-Palestine-Erekat)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- An Israeli soldier was killed and four others wounded
on Monday in a roadside bomb explosion in south Lebanon, Lebanon's
Voice of the People radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The bomb was detonated when an Israeli convoy passed by the
Hasbiyeh village in the eastern sector of the Israeli-occupied
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The wounded have been taken to a nearby hospital for treatment,
the radio said.
</P>
<P>
No group has claimed responsibility for the bombing.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen Israeli soldiers have been killed and 86 others wounded
in roadside bomb blasts in south Lebanon so far this year.
(Lebanon-Israel-Roadside Bomb)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- As most Arab countries urged Turkey and Syria to
exercise self-restraint and solve their crisis through diplomatic
means, Turkey softened its tone on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Air Force Commander Ilhan Kilic said in the
southeastern city of Diyarbakir that Turkey is a supporter of
peace, and believes bilateral disputes can be solved through
crisis management.
</P>
<P>
"If the problem is not solved through diplomacy, other methods
will follow, but the nation does not want war," he said.
(Turkey-Syria-Crisis)
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran on Monday reiterated its demands to punish the
killers of Iranian nationals in Afghanistan, return the bodies of
the other three victims and release other Iranians held by the
Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
"Iran's demands are the same of the international community
and the Taliban should submit to the international demands,"
Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi said during a meeting with United
Nations envoy on Afghanistan Lakhdar Brahimi.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi called on the world community to pressure the Taliban
into abiding by international will, particularly the U.N. Security
Council resolution 1193 urging the Afghan militia to stop
genocide, the official news agency IRNA reported. (Iran-UN
Envoy-Afghanistan)


