<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Marks 50 Years of Peacekeeping Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations on
Tuesday observed fifty years of peacekeeping operations by paying
tribute to all peacekeepers who have served since 1948, and
especially those who have died while serving under the United
Nations flag.
</P>
<P>
At a special meeting of the General Assembly, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan presented the first Dag Hammarskjold
Medals to the families of three United Nations officials who lost
their lives while pursuing peace missions.
</P>
<P>
The first medal was presented to the family of Dag
Hammarskjold, the second United Nations Secretary-General, for him
the prize is named -- who lost his life in a plane crash on
September 18, 1961 while on a mission to bring an end to fighting
in the Congo.
</P>
<P>
The second medal was received by the family of Commandant
Rene de Labarriere, the first peacekeeper to lose his life in a
United Nations peacekeeping operation. A French officer serving
as a Military Observer in the Untied Nations Truce Supervision
Organization in Palestine, Commandant de Labarriere was killed
by a landmine on July 6, 1948.
</P>
<P>
The third medal was presented to the family of Count Folke
Bernadotte, United Nations Mediator in Palestine, who was
assassinated on September 17, 1948 in Jerusalem while seeking a
negotiated settlement of the Palestine problem.
</P>
<P>
Dag Hammarskjold Medal is a new honor, established by
resolution of the United Nations Security Council in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
Since 1948, forty-nine peacekeeping operations have been
deployed by the Security Council, thirty-six of them in the past
decade. Today some 14,500 troops, military observers and
civilian police, 2,000 international civilian personnel and
3,700 local staff are serving in seventeen different missions.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,580 United Nations military and civilian peacekeepers
from some 85 countries have died while serving under the United
Nations flag during this half century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Tighten Control Over Alcohol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Under the new decree, licenses may be stripped for failing to
guarantee government control over alcohol production and trade.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Gennady Kulik said the presidential
decree and government resolution on alcohol production and sales
do not imply any "nationalization" of this industry.
</P>
<P>
He said that the main purpose of these documents is to
tighten control over this sphere at all stages.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with these documents, alcohol will be produced
by enterprises whose controlling block of shares is held by the
state, or by unitary enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Kulik noted that enterprises possessing state licenses will be
in charge of supplies of alcoholic drinks stronger than 28 proof.
</P>
<P>
He said prices on alcohol and alcoholic drinks will not
increase. On the contrary, the opportunity will arise to lower
prices on these products.
</P>
<P>
In the estimate of the Finance Ministry, the measures
stipulated is expected to add 30 to 35 billion rubles (about 4.8
to 5.6 billion U.S. dollars) to the state budget, Kulik said.
</P>
</TEXT>
