<HEADLINE> Bad Medicines Discovered Among Chinese Flood Relief Materials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Three pharmaceutical plants and
another company have been found guilty of providing false and
sub-standard medicines as relief materials for flood-damaged parts
of China, the State Bureau of Pharmaceutical Supervision and
Management announced today.
</P>
<P>
On August 26, the Hebei Provincial Medicine Company sent 2,278
boxes of medicines worth 1.46 million yuan (about 180,000 U.S.
dollars) to Anhui Province as disaster relief materials.
</P>
<P>
When the medicine arrived in Anhui, the local pharmaceutical
control department found that some of the packaging had been
seriously damaged and tests conducted by local laboratories showed
that some of the medicines, whose function was to prevent insect
bites, reduce inflammation, or treat colds and flu, had serious
quality problems.
</P>
<P>
An investigation by the State Bureau of Pharmaceutical
Supervision and Management revealed that the medicines had been
produced by three different factories in Hebei and Sichuan
provinces and that they were all either sub-standard or were fake
products.
</P>
<P>
The bureau has closed one of the factories and ordered the
other two to stop production and correct their problems and has
confiscated the money they made from the materials. The Hebei
Provincial Medicine Company was fined and ordered to stop
production to correct its ways.
</P>
<P>
All the false and sub-standard medicines in Anhui will be
destroyed by the local medical administration, the bureau says,
adding that such medicines, if found, in other areas will be
treated in the same way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
