<HEADLINE> Cook Says EU Backs Using Force in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook said Tuesday that European Union (EU) agreed that force must
be used if the Yugoslav government refused to comply with U.N.
Security Council resolutions on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to BBC radio from Luxembourg, Cook dismissed
suggestions that some EU members wanted further authorization from
the United Nations before force could be used to persuade Belgrade
to withdraw his security forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We want (Yugoslav President Slobodan) Milosevic to comply with
the United Nations resolution, to stop the hostilities, withdraw
his forces and allow the refugees to get home," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Cook, who is in Luxembourg attending a meeting of EU foreign
ministers, pointed out:"If he (Milosevic) will not do that without
the use of force, Britain is ready to back force. I got a very
clear message yesterday from that meeting that we are agreed on
the two important issues."
</P>
<P>
"First of all we are absolutely determined that Milosevic must
adhere to the Security Council resolution," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
"And secondly we are all agreed that if necessary, and none of
us wants to do it, force must be used to make him comply with the
Security Council resolution." 
</P>
