<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, Palestinians Have to Make 'Hard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERICO, WEST BANK, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Both Israel and the
Palestinians have to make "hard choices" in order to put the
peace process back on track quickly, U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
At a joint news conference with Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat after almost two hours of talks, Albright
said the time "is not on our sides" and therefore Israel and the
Palestinians have to move forwards the peace negotiations
quickly.
</P>
<P>
She declined to go into details about her meeting with Arafat
and the previous one held Tuesday morning with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, but said these meetings were
"useful."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary of state is on a mission trying to bring the
two sides closer to an agreement over the Israeli withdrawal from
the West Bank, which would pave the way for a four-day Middle East
summit in Washington in mid-October.
</P>
<P>
Progress has been reportedly made during the talks last week
in Washington between Arafat, Netanyahu and U.S. President Bill
Clinton, but Albright said it is still too early to say that
there will be an agreement when the three leaders are scheduled
to meet in Washington next week.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who arrived in Israel Monday night, held more than
two hours of inconclusive talks Tuesday morning with Netanyahu,
but there was no report of progress. She will meet Netanyahu
again in the evening.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said after his meeting with Albright that Israel had
met its obligation and now it was up to the Palestinians to
fulfill their commitments on fighting terrorism. But Arafat said
at the news conference in Jerico that "peace means security and
peace means freedom."
</P>
<P>
While the diplomatic shuttles are going on, clashes broke out
between Palestinians and Israeli soldiers again Tuesday in the
flashpoint West Bank town of Hebron, which has witnessed several
days of chaos since more than a dozen Israeli soldiers were
injured by a grenade attack last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a move which may worsen the situation, the Israeli
government decided Tuesday to build permanent houses on a Jewish
settlement in Hebron where a settler was killed in his mobile
house late August.
</P>
<P>
This was Albright's first trip to the region in over a
year. She is accompanied by Middle East envoy Dennis Ross and
Assistant Secretary of State Martin Indyk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
