<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis: Political Settlement to Turkish-Syrian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Amid mounting tensions between
Turkey and Syria, Egyptian President Hossni Mubarak arrived in
Ankara Tuesday in a bid to seek a way out to settle the crisis
politically.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak is to brief Turkish President Suleyman Demirel on the
outcome of his talks with Syrian President Hafez al-Assad last
Sunday. After his discussion in Ankara, he will fly back to
Damascus to convey the viewpoints of Turkey to al-Assad.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe despite harsh accusation exchanges
between the two countries and Turkish military buildup along the
Syrian border, diplomatic efforts still have the room of maneuver
to avoid a military confrontation between two neighboring Muslim
states.
</P>
<P>
Angered by Syria's alleged sheltering of Turkish Kurdish
rebels, Turkey took a tougher stand against Syria, but did not
reject political settlement to their disputes.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the Turkish private Star TV late Monday night,
Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz termed Syria the center of terrorism
in the Middle East, sheltering all terrorists in the region that
harbor the attempt to destroy peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
This is the latest accusation against Damascus by Turkish
leaders since Ankara massed heavy troops last week along its
border with Syria, for the first time, for military exercises,
which fueled their dispute.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long accused Syria of sheltering the PKK rebels, who
have been fighting since 1984 for autonomy for the Kurdish
minority in southeastern Turkey and frequently wage cross-border
raids on the Turkish military and civilian targets from their
camps in Iraq, Syria and Iran.
</P>
<P>
But Syria, together with Iran, has denied the charges, and
criticized, in return, Turkey for forming military alliance with
Israel that threatens the Arab security and undermines Syria's
bargaining position in the peace talks with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Many of the Arab states have voiced their concern over Turkey's
close military ties with Israel and deemed such a relationship a
threat to regional security.
</P>
<P>
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel accused Syria last Thursday
of trying provoke the Arab world to confront Ankara by using
Turkey's close ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
"This is not a friendly attitude. I declare to the world that
our patience is running out and we retain the right to retaliate
against Syria," Demirel said, threatening to use force to destroy
the alleged Kurdish bases within Syrian borders. .
</P>
<P>
The growing tensions aroused great concern among the Arab
countries, many of whom favor to keep Turkey, a predominantly
Muslim and politically secular state, as a friend, rather than
estranging it despite its close military ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
They called on the two neighbors exercise restraint and settle
their disputes by political means.
</P>
<P>
To react to the Arab concerns, Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem said Monday that Turkey will continue to take necessary
diplomatic ways to make Syria stop giving money, weapons and
logistics support to the PKK.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Foreign Ministry Spokesman Necati Utkan said Monday
that the hope for a diplomatic solution to the crisis has not come
to an end. "we will listen to President Mubarak. We expect
Mubarak to bring us information or at least impression," he added.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources here hold that Turkish side will ask Mubarak
to persuade Syria to make close cooperation with Turkey in
fighting the PKK while Syria will expect Turkey to make
compromises in sharing the water in the Euphrates River, which
originates in Turkey and flows down to Syria and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The Turkish-Syrian question is a complicated one, but it is not
impossible to solve through diplomacy," Egyptian Foreign Minister
Amr Moussa has put it. The world as whole is expecting good news
from Mubarak's shuttle diplomacy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
