<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai PM Does Not Plan to Stay in Power for Long </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai said Tuesday that he did not plan to stay in power until
the end of the present Parliament term in 2000 although his
coalition has received additional political support.
</P>
<P>
He said he would try his best to prepare the country for the
new election under the constitution.
</P>
<P>
Chuan made the remarks shortly after Monday's cabinet reshuffle
which brought in the National Development Party (NDP), although
known as the Chart Pattana Party, following a series of corruption
scandals that shock the coalition government.
</P>
<P>
The NDP, the third largest political party in Thailand, has 51
seats in the 389-strong Parliament, and its entry into the
government strengthens Chuan's cabinet, which leads a comfortable
majority over the 132-seat opposition.
</P>
<P>
Some 17 positions of ministers and deputy ministers were
involved in the reshuffle, the first of its kind by the Chuan
government since it came to power last November.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the reshuffle, Chuan denied that his coalition was
planning to secure its control on the House after recruiting the
support from the NDP.
</P>
<P>
"I have stressed to all (cabinet members) that we have a
limited time (before the current Parliament term expires)," said
Chuan, quoted by the Thai News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Political sources said Chuan's remarks indicated his intention
to hold elections ahead of schedule to ensure his Democrat Party's
long-term rule.
</P>
<P>
Chuan vowed to guarantee the unity in the government so as to
ensure efforts to implement its economic policies.
</P>
<P>
The political situation would not pose a problem if there was
good cooperation and coordination in the government, Chuan said.
</P>
<P>
The coalition government now consists of the Democrat Party,
Chart Pattana Party, Chart Thai Party, Social Action Party,
Solidarity Party, Seritham Party and a 12-MP group that defected
from the Prachakorn Thai Party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
