<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tightening Controls On Shipping Agents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- China's Vice-minister of
foreign trade and economic cooperation Sun Zhenyu said that China
will tighten controls on international shipping agents to create a
better environment for imports and exports because shipping is an
important link in foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Sun told a national conference on international shipping agents
that 1,542 enterprises in China have qualified as international
shipping agents since 1984 and that more than 80 percent of
China's imports and exports are now handled by these enterprises.
</P>
<P>
But, he said, the international cargo business in China is now
chaotic because of a lack of supervision and that some foreign
representatives in China do not have government approval and a few
enterprises are trying to attract clients with high commissions or
rebates.
</P>
<P>
Some enterprises have even tried to make a profit with special
invoices or by helping illegal businesses ship goods or clear
customs, he said.
</P>
<P>
These have seriously disturbed normal international cargo
operations, increasing costs and causing losses of state revenues,
he said, adding that foreign trade and economic cooperation
offices in various provinces and cities need to tighten controls
on the local shipping agents' business.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation is also
planning to establish a national cargo shipping association to
regulate and standardize the business, he said.
</P>
<P>
From January to August, China had 205.9 billion U.S. dollars
worth of exports and imports, a 5.5 percent growth over the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
However, Sun said, the rate of increase has been slipping month
by month, and the export situation is serious. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
