<HEADLINE> Chinese Official on Cross-Straits Political Negotiations (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Chen Yunlin, the director of the
State Council's Taiwan Affairs Office, said that Taiwanese
authorities need to make a positive response to the central
government's call for political negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Cross-Straits relations are currently at a critical historical
point, Chen told a plenary session of the First Council of the
Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS) here
today, and whether there will be sound relations in the 21st
century depends on whether the two sides can start political
negotiations as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the Taiwanese will actively respond
to the mainland's proposal to hold cross-Straits negotiations,
which he said are in line with the Taiwanese people's aspirations
for peace, stability, and better relations.
</P>
<P>
"We also hope that the Taiwan authorities can give up their
various attempts to hinder the development of cross-Straits
relations and prove their sincerity in improving relations and
seeking reunification of the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to ARATS President Wang Daohan, his association is
now looking forward to an early political dialogue with its
counterpart in Taiwan, the Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF), to
make preparations for cross-Straits political negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
