<HEADLINE> Beijing Needs More Trees To Deal With Polluted Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's Mayor Jia Qinglin said
today that the Chinese capital has a solution to its worsening air
problem and that is: plant more trees.
</P>
<P>
The fundamental way to deal with air pollution is increased
greenery, he said, while admitting that the amount of greenery in
urban areas is still low and that pollution has become a big
problem endangering the city's healthy development.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government is encouraging the planting of more
greenery around new buildings, and replacing old buildings with
trees.
</P>
<P>
Rapid urbanization and the construction of new roads and
buildings have been done at the expense of greenery, and there are
increasing complaints about the air problem caused by automobiles
and dust storms.
</P>
<P>
Forest coverage in Beijing is less than 40 percent and not more
than 35 percent in urban areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
