<P>
MANILA -- The Philippine Supreme Court Tuesday acquitted former
First Lady Imelda Marcos of corruption, saving her from a 12-year
jail term.
</P>
<P>
The ruling also overturned the only case in which Imelda had
been found guilty of graft during her late husband's 20-year rule
of the country. (Philippines-Imelda-Acquittal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- Lesotho political parties have agreed to a
proposal from the Southern African Development Community (SADC)
for the formation of a transitional structure to create conditions
for a new general election in the country.
</P>
<P>
The proposed transitional committee will comprise one or two
members from each party taking part in forthcoming election to be
held within 15 to 18 months, said a press report here Tuesday.
(SAfrica-Lesotho-New Election)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The Federal Assembly of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia Monday adopted a resolution on the Kosovo issue, saying
it backed the government's related position.
</P>
<P>
The resolution attributed the Kosovo crisis to the separatist
motives of the Kosovo ethnic Albanians, who want to break away
from the Yugoslav Federation, Tanjug news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav armed forces have taken measures of "needed depth and
scope" to curb "criminal activities" of the ethnic Albanians and
"terrorist gangs" in Kosovo, the resolution said, giving full
affirmation of the efforts in this regard by the Yugoslav armed
forces and Serbia's Interior Ministry. (Yugoslavia-Resolution)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz has said that
Syria is the center of terrorism in the Middle East and it
shelters all the terrorists.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the Turkish private Star TV late Monday night,
Yilmaz said that Syria is the country that not only shelters the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), but also many other
terrorist organizations. (Turkey-Syria-Accusation) 
</P>
