<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Federal Security Service Restructured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Federal Security
Service is facing restructuring under a decree issued by President
Boris Yeltsin on Tuesday, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The security service will consist of a chairman, two first
deputy directors, six deputy directors heading departments and two
deputy directors serving as the chiefs of the Moscow and St
Petersburg branches.
</P>
<P>
A 17-member board will be formed by the chairman, his deputies
and several other top officers, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's decree would "significantly boost the status" of the
security service chiefs in Russia's two largest cities, Interfax
quoted service Chairman Vladimir Putin as saying.
</P>
<P>
General Nikolai Patrushev, who was recently appointed chief
of the presidential department controlling regional officials, has
returned to the security service in the post of deputy director in
charge of economic crimes.
</P>
<P>
The combination of servicing divisions allowed for a reduction
of personnel and the funds released would strengthen the
operational units, Putin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
