<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Bans Release Of Starr Report (Chinese Version) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese version of the Starr
Report on President Bill Clinton's sexual activities has been
banned in China, today's Beijing Morning Post reported.
</P>
<P>
At 3:40 p.m. Monday, the Office Against Pornography and
Illicit Publications of the Municipal Press and Publications
Administration confiscated a number of Chinese copies of the Starr
Report, the newspaper said in its story.
</P>
<P>
According to Beijing Morning Post, the report was published by
a weekly newspaper as a "special issue" on September 28. It took
the newspaper only two days to translate the report from an
Internet copy.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a State Press and Publications
Administration official as saying newspapers can not publish a
book and release it nationwide and that the Chinese version of the
Starr Report should be regarded as an illicit publication.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that although the State Press and
Publications Administration has issued a circular banning the
publication of a Chinese version of the Starr Report out of some
"diplomatic reasons", a dozen publishing houses are now still
translating and compiling the report.
</P>
<P>
One vendor told the paper: "I started selling this book from
October 2, and it was selling extremely well. I had no problem of
selling 100 to 200 copies a day." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
