<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Backs Egypt in EU Anti-dumping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has British support in its
bid to abort the proposal by some European Union countries to
impose anti-dumping tariffs on Egyptian textile exports, a
British diplomat said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Head of the trade mission at the British Embassy in Cairo David
Rider told the Egyptian Middle East News Agency (MENA) that his
government was trying to convince other EU countries to vote in
favor of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
"Britain believes that imposing additional tariffs is not the
ideal way of dealing with dumping cases. We hope that other EU
members would respond favorably to this viewpoint and consider
other alternatives to resolve this issue in the near future,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, EU foreign ministers Monday rejected
a European Commission proposal to impose five-year anti-dumping
duties averaging 12 percent on imports of unbleached cotton
fabrics from five developing countries, including Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Officials attending the Luxembourg meeting said ministers from
the 15-nation bloc decided not to go ahead with the European
Commission's proposal for duties on "grey cloth" imports from
China, Egypt, India, Indonesia and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The proposal to impose anti-dumping tariffs on Egyptian textile
exports made on July 29 has soured the trade climate between Egypt
and the EU, particularly at talks on a partnership accord on trade
liberalization and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
EU ambassadors in Cairo last week met Egypt's Supply and Trade
Minister Ahmed Goweili, who had warned them that Egypt would
retaliate if the EU adopted the proposed duties, backed by cotton
producers in Italy, France, Portugal and Spain.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade between Egypt and Britain amounts to 5
billion Egyptian pounds (1.47 billion U.S. dollars) annually.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian exports to Britain rose by 19 percent in the last
seven months compared to the corresponding period last year. They
included crude oil and its derivatives, fresh vegetables and
fruits, textiles and ready made clothes.
</P>
<P>
The EU is Egypt's main trading partner and accounts, along with
the United States, for about 60 percent of exports. Egypt's annual
imports from the EU averages 5 billion dollars, while exports are
about 1.7 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
