<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "British Law Week" Opens in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 6 (Xinhua) -- "British Law Week" opened in
Beijing today and will run through Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Liu Yang, Vice-Minister of Justice, said at the opening
ceremony that the Chinese government considers Sino-British
relations important and the successful resolution of the Hong Kong
issue paved the way for new development of relations.
</P>
<P>
Britain originated the Anglo-American legal framework and its
legal system is well organized, Liu said, and China seeks to learn
from the experiences of others in establishing a system of rule of
law under the principle of mutual respect, equality, mutual
benefit, seeking common ground while reserving differences, and
common prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Lord Justice Otton, who is head of the British delegation to
"Law Week," said that the legal systems of Britain and China have
sharp differences. However, both systems have shown flexibility in
adapting to new concepts and different ways of thinking, he added.
</P>
<P>
"British Law Week" will have a simulated criminal trial,
British style, as well as discussions of commercial law, criminal
procedures, administrative law, relations between domestic law and
international covenants, the prosecutorial system, law and
policing, legal education, and human rights protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
