<HEADLINE> Turkey, Syria Urged to Settle Differences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government Tuesday
called on Turkey and Syria to settle their differences through
peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, government spokesman
Christos Stylianides stressed that each country's territorial
integrity should be respected.
</P>
<P>
"Countries should not resort to threats of force or the use of
force. Any differences should be resolved through
U.N. procedures," Stylianides said.
</P>
<P>
He added that "there are peaceful procedures and we believe
Turkey should act within this framework."
</P>
<P>
Tensions are mounting between Damascus and Ankara after they
traded accusations against each other, and Turkey has reportedly
massed up troops along its border with Syria.
</P>
<P>
The two neighbors have long been at odds over issues including
Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), water sharing and
the Turkish-Israeli military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has accused Syria of harboring PKK rebels, who have been
fighting since 1984 for an independent Kurdish state in the
southeast of Turkey. Syria has denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
Syria has lashed out at Turkey, a predominantly Muslim
country, for forming a military alliance with Israel, saying that
it undermines its bargaining position in negotiations with the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Syria has disputes with Israel over the future of the Golan
Heights, captured by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war. Damascus
insists on its return as a condition for peace with the Jewish
state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore, Second Fastest Aging Country in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE October 6 (Xinhua) -- A senior Singapore official
said here Tuesday that his country is in fact the second fastest
aging country in Asia after Japan.
</P>
<P>
Robert Loh, president of the National Council of Social Service
of Singapore, said at a press conference Tuesday, "It is estimated
that in the year 2030, about one million Singaporeans will be 60
years and older."
</P>
<P>
In mid-1996, Singapore's population was officially estimated at
3.04 million with an increase of about 1.9 percent over the
previous year and the proportion of residents aged 60 years and
over amounted to ten percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
In light of the rapidly growing aging population, the Retired &AMP;
Senior Volunteer Program (RSVP) will be officially launched by
Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong at the end of October as a
kick-start event for the U.N.-sponsored International Year of
Older Persons in Singapore, RSVP Singapore President Philbert Chin
announced at the press conference.
</P>
<P>
The launch of RSVP Singapore will be proceeded by a public
symposium under the theme "The age of challenge, the Challenge of
Age," he added.
</P>
<P>
Chin emphasized that "RSVP seeks to challenge the view that
older people are a liability in the community, always on the
receiving end of service from others, unappreciative and unable to
move with change."
</P>
<P>
He noted that RSVP Singapore, formed under the auspices of the
National Council of Social Service and supported by the Ministry
of Community Development, is a non-profit and privately financed
organization which offers older men and women the opportunity to
share their lifetime experiences, time and talents to enhance
their community through volunteer service.
</P>
<P>
Under its action plan, RSVP Singapore has four programs in
place, including Cyberguide Program, Mentoring Program, Senior
Executive Program and Club Service Program.
</P>
<P>
Chin said RSVP aims to add more vibrance to the lives of senior
citizens by providing them with opportunities to share their lives
with dignity through volunteer service and its projects have been
designed with the view of encouraging senior citizens in Singapore
to continue contributing to the community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
