<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Talks With Non-European Car Makers on Emission Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
started talks with non-European car makers on carbon dioxide
emission reductions in future exports to the union.
</P>
<P>
European Transport Commissioner Neil Kinnock said Tuesday talks
were underway between the EU and Japanese and South Korean
manufacturers after the the European council of transport
ministers approved the European Commission's agreement with the
European Automobile Manufacturers Association (EAMA) on
voluntarily reducing carbon dioxide emissions from new passenger
cars to 140 grams per kilometer by 2008.
</P>
<P>
The level will be further cut to 120 grams per kilometer by the
year 2010, Kinnock added.
</P>
<P>
So far, the agreement applies only to European car makers
affiliated with the EAMA which includes BMW, Fiat, Ford of Europe,
GM Europe, Daimler-Benz, Porsche, PSA Peugeot Citroen, Renault,
Rolls-Royce, Volkswagen and Volvo.
</P>
<P>
Kinnock said that details would be worked out for the talks
with non-EAMA car makers including those in the United States.
</P>
<P>
He hailed the agreement as a major contribution toward the
European Union's realization of its commitment to the Kyoto
Protocol.
</P>
<P>
The protocol, adopted in Japan on December 1997, sets legally
binding targets for developed countries for the post-2000 period
on reducing the emission levels of key greenhouse gases, such as
carbon dioxide.
</P>
<P>
The protocol called on developed countries to reduce their
combined emissions of six key greenhouse gases by at least five
percent below 1990 levels by the period 2008 to 2012.
</P>
<P>
Kinnock said that further discussions with non-EAMA
manufacturers would be held in December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Share Certificate in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's Feile Audio
Technology Company does not stand out among the 800-some companies
listed on China's stock exchanges, but it was Feile who issued the
first share in the Chinese mainland more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
That was in 1984. A piece of blue paper with the company's
name, face value, seal of the general manager, and the signature
of the stock holder on one side and tables for recording transfers
on the other.
</P>
<P>
In October of 1986, it was presented to the Chairman of the New
York Stock Exchange during his visit to Beijing. For the first two
days, few people came to the office on Wuyi Street where stocks
were sold.
</P>
<P>
But on the third day, crowds of people suddenly lined up
outside the office, one employee recalls, and in one day, 500,000
certificates selling for 50 yuan (about 6 U.S. dollars) each were
sold.
</P>
<P>
At that time, Chinese were still arguing about whether stocks
were capitalist and about why China didn't have any corporation
laws. But the first group of shareholders smelled the golden
opportunity and made the plunge.
</P>
<P>
Shares were similar to bonds at the beginning and shareholders
only got profits from the company before the stock exchange was
set up in November of 1986.
</P>
<P>
Feile was one of the first two companies listed and the funds
raised in the stock exchange have promoted its development. Its
capital has increased from 500,000 yuan to 150 million yuan and
the value of its shares has increased by more than 1,600 yuan.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, China had 810 companies listed on the
Shanghai and Shenzhen stock exchanges. The total value of stocks
was 210.9 billion yuan and market capitalization last year was
2.17 trillion yuan, or 23 percent of China's GDP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
