<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Calls Chirac on Settlement of Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
convinced French President Jacques Chirac on Tuesday that the
Kosovo conflict could be resolved without use of force through
Russia's efforts.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency reported Yeltsin informed Chirac by
telephone of Russia's latest attempts to ensure a political
settlement of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the Russian president stressed the
agreements reached between the Russian delegation and Yugoslav
authorities in Belgrade on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslavian leadership began on October 5 to take concrete
steps towards normalizing the situation in Kosovo, he said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also noted the decision of the Yugoslavian government
to invite observers from the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) to monitor troop withdrawals from the
province.
</P>
<P>
It allowed the international community "a real chance to take
part in the monitoring of the situation in that territory", he
said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the plans to settle the crisis by force would
not only fail to normalize the situation, but would bring about
grave international consequences.
</P>
<P>
Chirac, on his part, positively assessed the changes in the
stand of the Yugoslav leadership and expressed hope that it would
fulfill the resolution of the U.N. Security Council and ensure the
prompt opening of negotiations with the Kosovo Albanians on their
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
Both leaders agreed to keep up close contacts and coordinate
their efforts to settle the situation.
</P>
<P>
The Tuesday telephone conversation was one of a series of
contacts by Yeltsin with world leaders in an effort to head off
the threat of NATO action against Serbian forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Russian president held telephone talks with German
Chancellor Elect Gerhard Schroeder, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan and U.S. President Bill Clinton on Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
Also on Monday, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov held
telephone talks on Kosovo with his German and Italian counterparts
Klaus Kinkel and Lamberto Dini, and NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
