<HEADLINE> No Permit for Malaysia's Ruling National Front Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Police said Tuesday no
permit would be issued for the ruling 14-party Barisan Nasional
(National Front) rally planned for Saturday at the National
Stadium in Bukit Jalil here.
</P>
<P>
Police decided not to issue the permit for reasons of security,
the Malaysian national news agency Bernama reported, quoting Kuala
Lumpur Police Chief Kamaruddin Md Ali.
</P>
<P>
"The police wish to advise members of the public not to go to
the stadium at the stipulated time as the police had not issued a
permit for the gathering," the police officer was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The organizers have been informed of the police decision, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The gathering's coordinating committee chairman Najib Tun
Razak, who is education minister, said Monday that some 150,000
people were expected to attend the rally which Najib said was to
express support for Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad and would last
two hours.
</P>
<P>
United Malays National Organization (UMNO), the backbone
component of the National Front, was to be represented by more
than 50,000 members, the Malaysian Chinese Association, the second
largest component party of the Front, by up to 30,000 members, and
the Malaysian Indian Congress by 10,000 of its members, while the
other National Front component parties and the public will make up
the rest.
</P>
<P>
Kamarudin said police had also not issued permits to organizers
who had planned gatherings at the Merdeka Stadium, Merdeka Square,
Jalan Tunku Abdul Rahman and other venues in the capital city on
the same day.
</P>
<P>
Supporters of former deputy prime minister Anwar Ibrahim had
been distributing pamphlets announcing gatherings in the various
venues on October 10.
</P>
<P>
The police officer said, "Any attempt by anyone including the
organizers and members of the public to attend illegal gatherings
or rallies is an offense and action will be taken against them
under the Police Act." 
</P>
