<HEADLINE> Albright: Much to Be Done for Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said here Tuesday that there is still much work
to be done to push forward the peace talks between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after her meeting with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Albright said that both Israeli and
Palestinian leaders have to make hard decisions to break the
current deadlock over the Israeli troops' second redeployment in
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Albright arrived here Tuesday morning in an attempt to narrow
differences between the two sides ahead of a mid-October
Washington three-way summit to try to clinch a deal on the
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Netanyahu told reporters that if the Palestinians
fulfilled their commitments to ensure the security of the Jewish
country, there will be an agreement.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the possibility of a three-way meeting
between Albright, Palestinian National Authority President Yasser
Arafat and him on Wednesday is being checked.
</P>
<P>
Senior Palestinian sources have told Israel Radio that the
three-way meeting will be decided only after the meeting between
Albright and Arafat later Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have been stalled for 18
months and their dispute over the troops redeployment is the major
obstacle in reactivating the peace process.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. has put forward a proposal calling for an Israeli troop
pullback from 13 percent more of the West Bank in exchange for a
tougher Palestinian crackdown on Islamic militants. Palestinians
have accepted it.
</P>
<P>
Israel has initially rejected the formula and later promised to
hand over 10 percent of the land and set aside 3 percent as a
nature reserve under joint security control by both sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
