<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Hails Environmental Agreement With Car Makers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) transport
ministers Tuesday welcomed the environmental agreement between the
European Commission and the 11-member European Automobile
Manufacturers Association (ACEA).
</P>
<P>
The agreement limits carbon dioxide emission from new passenger
cars to 140 grams per kilometer in the EU by 2008 with a further
reduction to 120 grams per kilometer by 2010.
</P>
<P>
The transport ministers described the European Commission's
agreement with car makers as a substantial contribution to the
EU's commitment to the Kyoto Protocol.
</P>
<P>
Under the protocol, developed countries are bound to reduce
their combined emissions of six key greenhouse gases by at least
five percent below 1990 levels by 2008 to 2012.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European
Union, had to submit the agreement to the European council of
transport ministers and the European Parliament before it is
finalized.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's council meeting expressed satisfaction at the
agreement which was designed to make a major contribution to
reducing the average carbon dioxide emissions of newly-registered
passenger cars to 120 grams per kilometer by 2010 at the latest as
called for by the council.
</P>
<P>
The council requested the commission in its scheduled 2003
review to evaluate progress toward reaching the emission target.
</P>
<P>
The EU transport ministers said after the meeting that the
emission accord was only one element of EU efforts to control
carbon dioxide emissions from the transport sector.
</P>
<P>
They underlined the need for a comprehensive policy approach
and confirmed their intention to progress with the commission's
agreement on a community policy to be worked out by the council.
</P>
<P>
The ACEA members include BMW, Fiat, Ford of Europe, GM Europe,
Daimler-Benz, Porsche, PSA Peugeot Citroen, Renault, Rolls-Royce,
Volkswagen and Volvo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
