<HEADLINE> Singapore's Lee Says Asian Countries to Recover in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Senior Minister Lee
Kuan Yew has said economic growth would resume in Asian countries
and their recovery from the current economic crisis would vary
from country to country.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in an interview with The Australian, the
transcript of which was released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Growth would resume but the price of restructuring must be
paid, he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
He added that the economic crisis had thrown Asian confidence
temporarily off balance and it would take a couple of years for
every one to sort his position out.
</P>
<P>
But the basic virtues such as hard working, the willingness to
learn and welcoming foreign investments had not disappeared, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The senior minister said recovery from the crisis that has been
reeling Asia for more than a year would depend on political
stability and a return of confidence following fundamental
restructuring of their financial institutions and major
corporations.
</P>
<P>
Referring to currency and capital controls exercised by
Malaysia, he said Malaysia's experience would be closely watched
by other countries.
</P>
<P>
If Malaysia's economy improved, he said, other countries would
follow suit.
</P>
<P>
Taking the case in Japan, Lee said the region will not see a
reform of Japanese banking system, the kind the Americans believe
is necessary.
</P>
<P>
Japanese culture was dictating why reform and recovery in Japan
would take longer, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the pace would be that of the slowest in their convoy
system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
