<HEADLINE> Swissair Offers Compensation for Victims' Families </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The families of the 229
passengers and crew who died on Swissair Flight 111 will each be
offered about 137,000 U.S. dollars in compensation in the coming
months, the Globe and Mail reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
They will be the first beneficiaries of an agreement made last
year by several major air carriers, including Swissair, to raise
the liability limit to about 137,000 dollars from the 75,000
dollars cap on damages that was set in 1966.
</P>
<P>
Since the Swissair jet crashed in the Atlantic Ocean off
Canada's coast on September 2, the airline has been under pressure
from some lawyers to announce that it would make the payments
regardless of any legal action planned by family members.
</P>
<P>
But Eric Amman, Swissair legal affairs manager for North
America, said the airline has been preoccupied with addressing the
aftermath of the tragedy and paying about 20,000 dollars per
family to cover the cost of travel and other expenses incurred
after the crash.
</P>
<P>
To date Swissair has paid out about 2.9 million dollars to 133
families and has received requests for assistance from 24 others.
</P>
<P>
The compensation under the international liability agreement
will cost Swissair's insurer about 31.3 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
