<HEADLINE> Mubarak Flies to Ankara on Mediation Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
left here Tuesday on a lightning visit to Ankara in a bid to
mediate in the escalating row between Syria and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian leader is accompanied by a delegation including
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, Minister of Information Safwat
al-Sherif, Presidential Political Advisor Osama al-Baz and head of
the presidential cabinet Zakarya Azmy.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that Mubarak is carrying to Ankara a plan on
gradual reconciliation between Turkey and Syria.
</P>
<P>
This plan might lead to holding a series of Turkish-Syrian
ministerial meetings, probably to be followed by a quadrilateral
summit that would include the leaders of Egypt and Saudi Arabia,
according to the Egyptian and Turkish press reports Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The trip followed talks between Mubarak and Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad in Damascus Sunday. Mubarak has called on both
sides to restrain from any provocative actions.
</P>
<P>
"President Mubarak will go to Turkey as representative of the
Arab side and chairman of the Arab summit that calls for peace in
the region," Moussa told reporters Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said Egypt is seeking to establish a mechanism for dialog
between the two neighbor countries and is going to "take it (the
problem) by the root."
</P>
<P>
Strained ties between Mideast neighbors Syria and Turkey have
deteriorated during the past weeks with Syria bridling at Turkey's
growing military links with Israel and Turkey threatening Damascus
for allegedly aiding Kurdish rebels fighting for autonomy in
southeast Turkey.
</P>
<P>
But both sides appear to have pulled back from the brink in
recent days with separate announcements that they seek diplomat
means to resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz said on Saturday that
Turkey plans a military exercise along the Syrian border after the
end of the current NATO exercises in the area.
</P>
<P>
Ankara also announced plans for fresh naval maneuvers in the
eastern Mediterranean and joint air exercises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
