<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oriental Thought May Influence World of 21st Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Traditional thought in the Far
East may in some way shape the world in the 21st century,
according to participants at a seminar here today.
</P>
<P>
Confucianism and Taoism, which both dominated much of Chinese
thinking throughout its history, and Buddhism, Islam, and Japan's
Shintoism influence not only 21st century Asia but the rest of the
world as well in its economy, social development, international
relations, and the environmental protection, they said.
</P>
<P>
The 2nd International Symposium on Oriental Thought started
Tuesday afternoon and will run through Thursday. It was organized
by the China International Culture Exchange Center and Japan's
Yasuda Fire and Marine Insurance Company.
</P>
<P>
Scholars and specialists from Japan, the Republic of Korea,
Singapore, China's mainland, the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region, and Taiwan are attending.
</P>
<P>
The first seminar of this series was held in Shanghai in 1996.
</P>
