<HEADLINE> Less Foreigners Visit Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam's
largest city, received more than 555,000 foreign visitors in the
first nine months of this year, a decrease of five percent from
the same period last year, Vietnam News Agency reported Tuesday,
quoting the city's tourism service.
</P>
<P>
Turnover from tourism services reached over 1.9 trillion VN
dong (138 million U.S. dollars) in the January-September period,
down by 13.3 percent from the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
Of the sum, foreign-invested tourism companies contributed 576
billion VN dong (41 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Average occupancy rate of Ho Chi Minh City's hotels was 37
percent in the first nine months of this year, a decrease of four
percent compared with the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
To attract more tourists, the city's tourism sector has
organized trips to the central highlands and the Mekong Delta, and
tours of Vietnam-Laos and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Ho Chi Minh City now has 151 traveling agencies and 484 hotels
with 14,300 rooms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
