<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmer Gets Airline Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A farmer in China's Zhejiang
Province recently signed a one-year contract with the local civil
aviation bureau to operate a regional passenger airline at a cost
of 10.8 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Chen Tianming, a farmer in the city of Yongkang, will operate
two roundtrip flights each week between the city of Quzhou in
southern Zhejiang, and Guangzhou, the capital of Guangdong
Province, beginning October 20.
</P>
<P>
Chen is practically alone in this business. He established a
decorating company in 1995 and made quite a profit from it. Later
he built a chartered airplane service and then decided to get
involved in civil aviation because he saw an increasing number of
local businessmen travelling to and from Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
"We'll work heart and soul for passengers and improve our
services steadily," he explains.  
