<HEADLINE> Portuguese PM Starts Visit to Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Portuguese Prime Minister
Antonio Guterres arrived in Maputo Tuesday morning, starting his
five-day official visit to Mozambique at the invitation of
Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral cooperative relations between Mozambique and
Portugal should be enhanced from a strategic point of view,
Mozambican newspaper Noticias quoted Guterres as saying in a
interview on the eve of his visit.
</P>
<P>
He said that he will propose to the Mozambican government
several cooperation programs for discussion.
</P>
<P>
As scheduled in the agenda, the Portuguese prime minister will
hold talks with President Chissano and his Mozambican counterpart
Pascoal Mocumbi. Guterres will also meet with Mozambican Speaker
of Parliament Eduardo Mulembwe and the leaders of some political
parties.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in the southern African country, the
Portuguese official will pay visits to four provinces, namely
Inhambane, Sofala, Tete and Namputa.
</P>
<P>
Portugal ranked the second among 10 major investors in
Mozambique, with a total investment of 130 million U.S. Dollars
in 198 projects. It is also one of the major trade partners of
its former colony.
</P>
<P>
Mozambiqu ranked the third among the Portuguese-speaking trade
partners of Portugal in 1997, right after Angola and Cape Verde.
</P>
<P>
The major products the southern African country exports to
Portugal include shrimp, cashew nut and cotton while the goods
Mozambique imports from the European country include machinery,
farm produces, textiles, leather goods and manufactured metal
products.
</P>
<P>
Portugal also offers scholarships for 600 Mozambican students
and researchers to study in its institutions each year.  
</P>
