<HEADLINE> Chinese, British Prime Ministers Hold Talks (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Blair expressed the hope that his current China visit will
further promote UK-China relations, and said UK-China ties have
entered a new era, which serves the interests of the people of
both countries and benefits the entire world.
</P>
<P>
Britain and China are taking concrete measures to step up
bilateral relations, Blair noted.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that President Jiang Zemin's visit to Britain next
year will be the first such trip by a Chinese head of state, and
that this will certainly have a far-reaching impact on
Sino-British ties.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement issued by the two countries today is a
significant document, guiding the direction of the development
of Sino-British ties across the century, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the establishment of a Sino-British
Forum will enable personnel from all walks of life in both nations
to express their ideas on bilateral ties, helping the sound growth
of Sino-British relations.
</P>
<P>
The British prime minister said that President Jiang Zemin's
visit to Britain next year will serve as a "landmark" in the
bilateral relationship, and that the British side eagerly awaits
the visit, which will promote UK-China relations.
</P>
<P>
Today's joint statement signals that the two countries will
engage in cooperation in a variety of areas, according to Blair,
and the bilateral forum will provide more opportunities for
increased exchanges of views.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers briefed each other on the political and
economic situations in their respective countries and discussed
the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Blair highly praised the Chinese government for not devaluing
its currency and for its role in helping those countries
affected by the financial crisis, both deserving of high
respect worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Zhu expressed his appreciation for the contribution made by
Blair and his Labor Party to the smooth return of Hong Kong. He
reiterated that the central government of China will adhere to the
principle of "one country, two systems" and will not interfere in
Hong Kong's affairs, which belong to the scope of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
Blair said that Hong Kong has had remarkable success since its
return, though it now faces economic difficulties because of the
Asian financial crisis. In fact, Hong Kong is doing a better job
than expected, he added.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of human rights, the two prime ministers agreed
that the two countries will continue dialogues.
</P>
<P>
Zhu praised Blair's efforts to help the European Union (EU)
improve its attitude toward China on human rights. Blair hailed
the fact that the Chinese government signed the International
Covenant on Civil and Political Rights, calling it an important
step.
</P>
<P>
After their talks, the two prime ministers met with Chinese and
British enterpreneurs.  
</P>
