<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Predicted to Be First Out of Economic Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Board of Investment
(BOI) Secretary General Staporn Kavitanon Tuesday voiced optimism
that his country was well on its way to being the first out of the
economic crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Staporn, in a speech to the 4th meeting of the British-Thai
Business Group being held here, said Thailand's macroeconomic
indicators showed "significant light at the end of the tunnel"
despite the fact that the country's Gross Domestic Product (GDP)
growth was likely to decline by around 8 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
"While the value of Thai exports is likely to decline in U.S.
dollar terms, the volume of exports has risen by an estimated 14
percent through the first seven months of 1998," he said. "Exports
of products such as computers, canned seafood, rubber products,
and automobiles and components are showing double-digit,
dollar-denominated growth and traditional exports such as rice and
garments are ahead of last year's pace."
</P>
<P>
The BOT chief said Thai exports to the European Union, which
account for some 16 percent of all Thai exports, increased 12.1
percent during the first half of 1998, and exports to the U.S. are
also up sharply.
</P>
<P>
He said the BOT estimates that full-year exports will exceed 53
billion U.S. dollars, which, when combined with declines in
imports, will result in a healthy trade surplus of about 11.5
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Staporn said that by year-end, the current account will show a
surplus of some 15 billion dollars, roughly 14 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed to the healthy flows of foreign direct
investment (FDI). For the first five months of 1998, Staporn
indicated that "BOT reported that FDI was roughly equivalent to
the full-year total of about 104 billion baht (2.67 billion
dollars) in 1997".
</P>
<P>
"After a period of unprecedented growth, Thailand is undergoing
a cyclical adjustment, from which we will soon emerge, and they
(foreign investors) are investing now in order to reap the rewards
when we do," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said many foreign-funded projects are investing needed
foreign currency into Thailand and are contributing to a more
stable baht, which has traded in a relatively narrow range,
between 28-42 to the U.S. dollar, for the past eight months,
despite concerns about the yen, the ringgit and other regional
currencies.
</P>
<P>
This stability, he said, had made it possible for the Bank of
Thailand to relax monetary policy, and interest rates have
declined dramatically and appear likely to continue to do so until
year-end.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, inflation in September was 7 percent and it is
quite likely that full-year inflation will be less than 9 percent,
well bellow the forecast by the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
As a whole, Staporn noted, these macroeconomic statistics
provide "reason for cautious optimism that we are working our way
out of the economic crisis". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
