<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kashmir Not Internal Matter of India: US Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Ambassador to India
Richard Celeste said Tuesday that the United States did not
consider Kashmir issue an internal matter of India.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference in Pune city about 1,500 km
southwest of New Delhi, he said it not only had regional but also
global ramifications.
</P>
<P>
He said that the fallout of nuclear tests performed by the two
countries in May this year is the mounting tension across the Line
of Control along the Kashmir area. With both countries now
possessing nuclear weapons any miscalculation could spell
disaster.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the only way in which the vexed problems
between the two countries could be sorted out is through bilateral
talks," he said adding that such talks would pay the way for
better understanding.
</P>
<P>
Since their division in 1947, India and Pakistan have had three
wars and two of them were over the Kashmir issue. Even today the
two countries still have a big gap over the issue. India maintains
that Kashmir is an integral part of its territory while Pakistan
says it is a disputed issue which is a root cause of tension
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have held various talks in the past in a bid
to improve their soured relations, yet their talks have failed so
far mainly because of their different perceptions on the Kashmir
issue.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, India has time and again said the Kashmir
issue is a bilateral issue and it should be solved through
bilateral talks between India and Pakistan. It opposes the
involvement of third force in it. Pakistan, however, has called
upon the world community to help solve the Kashmir issue. It said
that history shows that without third force, only Pakistan and
India could not solve the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine President Endorses Imelda's Acquittal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada Tuesday endorsed the acquittal of Imelda Marcos by the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
"I hope she will be happy about it. One thing I could see
there, according to the charges, there was conspiracy. But when
one is acquitted, the other one must be acquitted," the president
said.
</P>
<P>
Imelda, the 69-year-old widow of former president Ferdinand
Marcos, was accused of illegally entering into five contracts
unfavorable to the government during her husband's 20-year rule of
the country.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, the third division of the Supreme Court upheld
the 1993 ruling by an anti-graft court, sentencing her to a jail
term of 12 years. But her alleged accomplice, former
transportation minister Jose Dans, was acquitted.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said the two projects involved in the charge against
Imelda "really benefit the people."
</P>
<P>
However, he said the acquittal will not hamper the government's
efforts to recover Marcos' ill-gotten wealth hidden abroad. His
government is eyeing the resolution of the illegal wealth cases by
the end of this year, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Supreme Court Tuesday acquitted Imelda of the
graft charge, overturning the only case in which Imelda had been
found guilty of graft.
</P>
<P>
The court ruled 8-5, with one judge abstaining.
</P>
<P>
Marcos was ousted in a popular revolt in 1986. He fled to
Hawaii, the United States, and died there three years later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
