<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Committee to Be Set Up for New Elections in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho political parties
have agreed to a proposal from the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) for the formation of a transitional structure to
creat conditions for a new general election in the country.
</P>
<P>
The proposed transitional committee will comprise one or two
members from each party taking part in forthcoming election to be
held within 15 to 18 months, said a press report here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We will take it to the people... and if they say yes to it,
we will also say yes," opposition alliance spokesman Vincent
Malebo said Monday after a seven-hour meeting in the capital
Maseru.
</P>
<P>
He said that if the opposition alliance did not get a mandate
from its supporters, it would resort to other ways of overcoming
the political impasse in the country, Johannesburg-based
newspaper The Citizen reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ruling Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD)'s
deputy leader Kelebone Maope, said that his party did not in
principle have problems with the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the LCD and opposition parties in Lesotho
Monday held their second round of talks, chaired by South African
Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi, in a bid to
stabilize the political situation in the mountain kingdom.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the proposal announced by Mufamadi, the
transitional committee would help create conditions conducive to
the holding of free and fair elections for all parties.
</P>
<P>
The committee would also ensure equal treatment for all
political parties by state-owned broadcasting and information
services in the period leading up to the election.
</P>
<P>
It would make decisions on all electoral matters including the
role of the police, military services, intelligence services,
foreign services and media.
</P>
<P>
The committee would appoint a new independent electoral
commission to review Leostho's electoral system.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho, fully surrounded by South Africa, has been in
political crisis resulted from the allegations from opposition
parties that the May 23 general elections were rigged in favor of
the ruling LCD.
</P>
<P>
At the invitation of the Lesotho government, South Africa and
Botswana have deployed their troops in the country since
September 22 to help restoring law and order and to support the
legitimate government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
