<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, British Prime Ministers Hold Talks (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 6 (Xinhua)-- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji and
his British counterpart Tony Blair announced plans to establish
a Sino-British comprehensive partnership during their talks here
today.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have agreed that Chinese President Jiang Zemin
will pay a state visit to Britain in the latter half of 1999 at
the invitation of British Queen Elizabeth II.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers also announced plans to establish a
Sino-British Forum.
</P>
<P>
Zhu voiced his conviction that Blair's China tour, in which he
is accompanied by dozens of leaders of major British firms, will
forcefully push forward Sino-British cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
To increase Sino-British dialogue, consultation and cooperation
not only conforms to the fundamental interests of the two peoples,
but also benefits world peace, stability and development, Zhu
said.
</P>
<P>
Sino-British relations have witnessed a new chapter since the
smooth return of Hong Kong, Zhu said, adding that bilateral
cooperation in every area has seen remarkable progress with
frequent exchanges of high-level visits.
</P>
<P>
Five cabinet members of the British government, including the
vice prime minister and foreign minister, have visited China in
turn since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Sino-British economic and trade cooperation has also seen a
steady growth in recent years, with Britain becoming China's
second largest trading partner among European Union (EU) nations,
Zhu noted. Britain has become the EU's largest investor in China
this year, he added.
</P>
<P>
China and Britain are cooperating quite well in the fields of
chemicals, energy, telecommunications, education, culture,
science, technology, military, and sports, Zhu said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
