<HEADLINE> S. African Car Sales Drop in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- High interest rates in
South Africa are taking heavy toll of new vehicle sales, which
dropped by 27 percent in September this year against last year.
</P>
<P>
The National Association of Automobile Manufacturers of South
Africa (Naamsa) disclosed recently that the total new vehicle
sales, seen as an indicator of the economy's performance, plunged
to their lowest level in the year.
</P>
<P>
Only 22,882 units were sold, down 8,360 units compared to
September last year, the association reported.
</P>
<P>
Naamsa Director Nico Vermeulen said that the slow sales
reflected the effect of the restrictive monetary policy measures
implemented in response to the global financial instability.
</P>
<P>
The uncertain economic outlook and the exceptionally high
interest rate environment would result in continuing tough
conditions in the months ahead, said the Naamsa director.
</P>
<P>
One analyst here predicted that car sales would not recover
until the second quarter next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
