<HEADLINE> Former Tanzanian Minister Returns to Politics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's former
minister of industries and trade, William Shija, has come
back to political arena after he recaptured the Sengerema
parliamentary seat in a by-election.
</P>
<P>
Shija, a candidate for the ruling party Chama Cha Mapinduzi
(CCM), defeated his major opponent, Fortunatus Masha of the
United Democratic Party (UDP) in the by-election in Sengerema
constituency in the northern region of Mwanza last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports Tuesday, Shija scooped 29,345 votes
against Masha, who won 21,549 votes. Another candidate, Clement
Kamadi of the Civic United Front (CUF), got 789.
</P>
<P>
A total of 52,792 out of 61,156 registered voters cast their
votes in the by-election held on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Shija was ousted from the cabinet in July this year after the
High Court declared that his 1995 general elections results in
the constituency null and void.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Shija won over Masha with 19,917 against 13,080
votes. But Masha accused Shija of having irregularities in the
elections, saying that the latter did not resign his post as the
Mwanza Regional Commissioner before contested in the Sengerema
constituency, and that many polling stations were not opened in
time, making 17,489 registered voters fail to vote.
</P>
<P>
Based on these charges, the High Court unseated Shija who
automatically lost his ministerial post, which is currently held
by the Ilala MP, Iddi Simba.
</P>
<P>
The court also rejected Masha's plea of directly appointing
him as the member of parliament for Sengerema.
</P>
<P>
Following the nullification of the 1995 elections results,
Shija said that he did not intend to appeal against the High
Court judgement and would opt to contest the seat in a
by-election.
</P>
<P>
Shija said that he wanted to give voters in Sengerema a chance
to chose a candidate they wanted. As a result, he won again.
</P>
<P>
The UDP agents refused to sign the results form, apparently
alleging irregularities in the counting in the by-election.
</P>
</TEXT>
