<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Massive Privatization Kicks off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has formally put on sale
a host of key public enterprises, thus taking a concrete step in
its privatization program.
</P>
<P>
According to the advertisements on major national media
Tuesday by the Bureau of Public Enterprises, the government is
now inviting investors for a total of 41 firms.
</P>
<P>
These firms include the Nigerian Telecommunications Limited
(NITEL), the National Fertilizer Company Limited (NAFCON) and the
National Electric Power Authority (NEPA).
</P>
<P>
Three steel companies, three paper mills, five vehicle
assembly plants and two hotels are also for sale.
</P>
<P>
Besides the 41 companies, the Nigerian government also invites
for the building and operating of a second national
telecommunications network.
</P>
<P>
It also seeks the assistance of local and foreign accounting
firms, law practising firms, issuing houses, stock brokers,
merchant and investment banks and estate evaluators in the
privatization program.
</P>
<P>
According to the advertisements, the government will retain up
to 40 percent equity interest in the firms and give up 40 percent
to potential investors, while the left 20 percent will go to
Nigerian investors through the stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
The massive privatization and commercialization of public
enterprises were first announced by Nigerian leader General
Abdulsalam Abubakar on July 20 this year in a bid to revitalize
the country's ailing economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
