<HEADLINE> Myanmar, Chinese Company Sign Power Project Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar electric power
authorities and a Chinese Yunnan company reached a contract here
Tuesday on the implementation of the Paunglaung Hydroelectric
Power Project in Pyinmana, central Mandalay division of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony of the contract between the state-run
Myanmar Electric Power Enterprise (MEPE) and the Yunnan Machinery
and Equipment Import and Export Corporation (YMEIEC) of China was
attended by second secretary of the Myanmar State Peace and
Development Council Lieutenant-General Tin Oo, Deputy Prime
Minister Vice-Admiral Maung Maung Khin, Minister of Electric Power
Major-General Tin Htut, Senior Adviser of the Yunnan Provincial
Government Wang Xue Ren and Chinese Ambassador to Myanmar Liang
Dong.
</P>
<P>
Representing their respective parties, Director-General of the
MEPE U Yang Naing and President of the YMEIEC Lin Zai You signed
the contract.
</P>
<P>
According to the 160 million U.S. dollar contract, the YMEIEC
is to provide the complete set of machinery and equipment, design
underground factory and direct work implementation.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side will extend export credit, while the Myanmar
side be responsible for 2.75 percent of annual interest. The term
of repayment is 10 years with a grace period of 5 years.
</P>
<P>
The installed capacity of the Paunglaung project is 280
megawatts, accounting for 28 percent of Myanmar's existing
installed capacity.
</P>
<P>
The Paunglaung hydroelectric power station will mainly generate
electricity and will also possess agricultural irrigation
capacity.
</P>
<P>
Since 1989, the YMEIEC has been cooperating with Myanmar in
building hydroelectric power stations and has exported to the
country complete sets of related equipment for 17 small and medium
hydroelectric power stations, accounting for 94.4 percent of the
country's hydroelectric power projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Philippine First Lady Imelda Acquitted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Supreme Court
Tuesday acquitted former First Lady Imelda Marcos of corruption,
saving her from a 12-year jail term.
</P>
<P>
The ruling also overturned the only case in which Imelda had
been found guilty of graft during her late husband's 20-year rule
of the country.
</P>
<P>
The court ruled 8-5, with one judge abstaining, to acquit the
69-year-old widow of the late president Ferdinand Marcos.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, her motion for reconsideration is granted. Imelda
Marcos is acquitted," the Supreme Court said in its decision.
</P>
<P>
Imelda and her lawyers were not present when the decision was
released by the Supreme Court. But she received a telephone call
informing her of her acquittal.
</P>
<P>
An anti-graft court found Imelda guilty on two corruption
charges in 1993.
</P>
<P>
In January this year, a Supreme Court division acquitted her on
one charge but upheld her conviction on the second charge which
carried a maximum prison term of 12 years.
</P>
<P>
According to the charge, Imelda and former transportation
minister Jose Dans illegally entered into five unfavorable
contracts involving a government-run commuter railway and the
private Philippine General Hospital Foundation.
</P>
<P>
Imelda, who has been free on bail, appealed the ruling to the
entire Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
In a 23-page ruling, the Supreme Court said that Imelda did not
personally sign the lease and it was not proven that the lease
price was "grossly and manifestly disadvantageous" to the
government as prosecutors had argued.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court said the anti-graft court also violated rules
of due process in reaching its verdict.
</P>
<P>
"That is the last word on the matter. The Supreme Court has
spoken and that's it," said Francis Garchitorena, the chief judge
of the anti-graft court.
</P>
<P>
Marcos was ousted in a popular revolt in 1986. He fled to
Hawaii, the United States, and died there three years later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Absent From 2nd European Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUXEMBOURG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkey, for which the
European Conference was conceived as somewhat a consolation for
its not being included in the formal group of the European Union
(EU) membership applicant countries, did not attend on Tuesday the
second such conference.
</P>
<P>
The absence of Turkey indicated that problems still lingered in
the relations between the 15-nation union and the country that is
a long-time aspirant for a union membership and has been for long
a full member of NATO.
</P>
<P>
The EU-Turkey relations went sour after the EU extended
accession invitation last December to Poland, Hungary, the Czech
Republic, Slovenia, Estonia and Cyprus, and put Bulgaria, Romania,
Latvia, Lithuania and Slovakia on hold for later on, leaving but
Turkey out in the cold.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that the EU soon announced the creation of the
European Conference as a soothing compensation for its anguish,
Turkey declined the invitation to attend the inaugural conference
held in March this year in London at the level of heads of state
and government.
</P>
<P>
Matters turned worse for Turkey as the general affairs council
of the EU foreign ministers received Monday an accession progress
report on only the Greek Cypriot part of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The EU foreign ministers regretted the fact that the European
Commission's analytical examination of the pre-accession screening
could not cover Cyprus as a whole and that the invitation of the
Cyprus government to include representatives of the Turkish
Cypriot community in the negotiations had so far not been taken up.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing held after Monday's general affairs council
meeting, Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos did not rule
out the possibility of starting the ministerial level accession
negotiation in November with the partially-represented Cyprus and
of even taking it as such into the fold of the union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese FM Spokesman on U.S. Anti-China Clauses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Ministry
spokesman Zhu Bangzao said he hopes the government of the United
States take effective measures to prevent the anti-China clauses
from becoming law.
</P>
<P>
He also hopes the United States stick strictly to the
principles defined in the three joint communiques between the two
countries and relevant commitments made by the U.S. on the Taiwan
issue, and refrain from transferring the Theater Missile Defense
(TMD) system and related technology and equipment, and selling
advanced weapons to Taiwan, in order to avoid any damage to
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Zhu made the statement here this afternoon at the beginning of
his regular press conference.
</P>
<P>
He said the 1999 fiscal year National Defense Department
Authorization Act passed recently by the U.S. House of
Representatives and the U.S. Senate, contains some anti-China
clauses, and this act also calls for the integration of Taiwan
into the TMD and a continuation of arms sales to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
"This practice wantonly violated the basic norms of
international law and seriously violated the principles set out in
the three joint communiques between China and the U.S.," Zhu
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that if this act becomes law, it will create
obstacles to the improvement and development of
Sino-U.S. relations, and will also be detrimental to the security
and stability of Taiwan and the Asia-Pacific region, stressing
that "the Chinese side hereby expresses a deep concern and strong
opposition to this." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Fall by Nearly one Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Falls in major stocks,
particularly global media giant News Corp, pushed the Australian
sharemarket almost one percent lower Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index finished 24.5 points lower to 2491.2,
its lowest close since September 11.
</P>
<P>
"Concerns on overseas markets are still lingering and to the
extent that further falls are there, we will fall into line with
them," Jack Moss from Shaw Stockbroking said.
</P>
<P>
"Some of the blue-chips got into all sorts of trouble today but
this market could turn around very very quickly," he said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index closed 51.8 points down at 4338.9.
</P>
<P>
The News Corp fell 63.2 cents to 9.40 Australian dollars on a
turnover of 4.26 million shares while the preferred shares were 44
cents lower at 8.14 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The company's exposure to the British economy and a decision to
float just 13 percent of its Fox assets rather than the previously
mooted amount of up to 20 percent were seen as explanations for
the fall.
</P>
<P>
Among Australia's major banks, Westpac's 21 cent fall to 8.80
Australian dollars and National Australia Bank's 37 cent drop to
19.07 Australian dollars were the major moves.
</P>
<P>
ANZ bank was seven cents lower at 8.58 Australian dollars on a
turnover of 5.6 million shares while Commonwealth added 2.5 cents
to 18.52 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index was down just 0.8 points to 1008.1 as a
strong rise in resources giant BHP offset the gold sector's
reversal of fortune.
</P>
<P>
BHP jumped 28 cents to 11.98 Australian dollars on a view it
had been oversold of late, and the rise again prompted thought the
company had found a new chief after a search of more than six
months.
</P>
<P>
The gold index dropped 37.6 points to 1207.0, losing more than
three quarters of Monday's rise, as the spot bullion price fell
3.30 U.S. dollars per ounce to 296.40 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was 272.77 million shares traded at a value of 557.54
million U.S. dollars, with 637 falls, 457 rises and 324 steady.
</P>
