<HEADLINE> Nigeria Denies Amassing Troops on Disputed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Defense Headquarters
has denied Cameroon's allegation that Nigeria is amassing troops
on the disputed Bakassi Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Acting Defense Director of Information Sam Tella said
Monday that Cameroonian Defense Minister Amadou Ali had advised
the country's soldiers "to be on the alert as Nigeria amasses
troops on the disputed peninsula."
</P>
<P>
Tella described Cameroon's allegation as untrue, stressing
that "Nigeria has not and is not contemplating a military
build-up anywhere around Bakassi."
</P>
<P>
"In fact, we see no reason for such action," Nigeria's Daily
Times newspaper Tuesday quoted Tella as saying.
</P>
<P>
He noted Nigeria still believes that the Bakassi issue could
be solved peacefully.
</P>
<P>
According to a Cameroonian newspaper Herald report,
Cameroonian Defense Minister Amadou Ali said that "the Bakassi
Peninsula is so strategic and belongs to Cameroon till the
International Court of Justice proves the contrary."
</P>
<P>
Last month, Nigeria accused Cameroon of amassing troops at the
border and also accused Cameroonian gendarmes of attacking
Nigerian fishing towns in the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The dispute over the Bakassi Peninsula between Nigeria and
Cameroon has been brought to the International Court of Justice
in a bid to seek a peaceful solution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
