<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Textile Industry Market to Become Broader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese textile expert
predicts China's demand for textile machinery will increase in two
years when the national drive to cut down outmoded spindles is
complete.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Yankai, a ranking official of the China Council for the
Promotion of International Trade (CCPIT), said the spindle-cut
move does not mean a decline for the country's textile industry.
</P>
<P>
"The retrenchment in China's textile industry mainly covers the
spinning sector, while other sectors such as weaving, dyeing and
garment-making will maintain a steady growth," Zhang said during a
news conference at the Sixth China International Textile Machinery
Exhibition (CITME) held here today.
</P>
<P>
Zhang went on to say that rural enterprises and joint-ventures,
accounting for two-thirds of China's textile industry, will have a
great demand for new textile equipment and techniques.
</P>
<P>
China's textile industry is the largest in the world. However,
it has suffered losses for years because of poor management and
outmoded equipment.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing structural adjustment of the textile industry
constitutes a significant reform of the losing state-owned
enterprises in China, Zhang said, adding that the CITME '98 offers
a good chance to revitalize China's textile industry and upgrade
the technology of Chinese enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The CITME '98 will be held at the International Exhibition
Center in Beijing from October 13 to 17. It will be the largest
textile machinery exhibition ever held in China and the fourth
largest in the world, Zhang noted.
</P>
<P>
Some 700 manufacturers from 22 countries and regions will
attend the exhibition, including state delegations from major
textile machinery manufacturing countries including Germany, Japan
and the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Chinese manufacturers will make up one-quarter of all
participants and their products represent the highest quality in
China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
