<HEADLINE> World Habitat Day Observed in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie Tuesday pledged to continue rehabilitating the capital
city's slum areas to turn them into a suitable place to live in.
</P>
<P>
"One way of doing this is to build simple apartment buildings,"
Habibie said in observance of World Habitat Day 1998 as he opened
a seminar on housing at the State Palace here.
</P>
<P>
"This effort should involve not only the government but the
private sector and the people as well, because without them, it
would be difficult to create a comfortable and peaceful city for
us to live in," the president added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that improving the city's physical appearance needs
expertise and urban planning.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's cities naturally evolved from villages into small,
medium and big ones, he said.
</P>
<P>
Because there was no urban planning, the village turned into a
crowded city, he said, adding that improving such kind of place
would cost a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that rehabilitation is a must.
</P>
<P>
Citing a 1985 United Nations resolution, Habibie also reminded
of the need to increase the people's awareness of preserving their
environment.
</P>
<P>
In his address, State Minister for Housing and Settlement Theo
L. Sambuaga said his ministry is planning to build 100,000 units
of simple and very simple houses this fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
