<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10 Banking Institutions in Malaysia to Be Recapitalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Ten more banking
institutions in Malaysia will undertake recapitalization exercise
in a bid to enhance their resilience, Danamodal Nasional Bhd
announced here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Danamodal, set up on August 10 for bank recapitalization in the
country, signed Tuesday conditional agreements with the
institutions -- Arab-Malaysian Bank, Arab-Malaysian Finance,
Arab-Malaysian Merchant Bank, MBf Finance, BSN Commercial Bank,
Oriental Bank, United Merchant Finance, Perdana Merchant Bankers,
Sabah Bank and Utama Merchant Bank Bhd, its Managing Director
Mohamad Daud Hj Dol Moin announced in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Based on preliminary estimates, Danamodal was expected to
invest about 3.3 billion ringgit (about 868.421 million U.S.
dollars) in the institutions, Mohamad Daud said, adding the
investment may be in the form of various capital instruments,
including but not limited to equity, debt or a hybrid of equity
and debt.
</P>
<P>
He said the injection of fresh capital would help the
institutions to refocus on intermediation activities and the
recapitalization of these 10 institutions is a pre-emptive move to
enhance the resilience of the institutions which are basically
sound.
</P>
<P>
The recapitalization of Malaysia's banking system is a key
recommendation in the National Economic Recovery Plan recently
released by the National Economic Action Council which is of the
view that recapitalization, rather than intermittent regulatory
interventions, will restore public confidence in the safety and
soundness of the banking system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
