<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Economy Projected to Shrink 1.8 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Economic Planning Agency
(EPA) revised Tuesday its initial projection of 1.9 percent growth
for the country's economy in fiscal 1998 to an inflation-adjusted
1.8 percent contraction, the biggest shrinkage on record.
</P>
<P>
The contraction, tallied on gross domestic product (GDP), or
the total value of goods and services produced in the country,
would mark two straight years of negative growth for the first
time since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
"There will be a showdown for the Japanese economy's
regeneration from the second half of fiscal 1998 through fiscal
1999," EPA chief Taichi Sakaiya told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The EPA's latest projection for fiscal 1998, through March
1999, is roughly in line with others of the kind by private
economists that reflect the current economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
"The Japanese economy should be able to post positive growth in
the next fiscal year," if various stimulus plans are fully
executed, the top government economic planner predicted.
</P>
<P>
The latest revision of the economic-growth projection, the
ninth downward since fiscal 1959, uses latest available data.
</P>
<P>
Slack domestic demand contributes minus 2.4 percentage points
to the projected 1.8 percent contraction, including minus 0.5
point from consumer spending, minus 0.5 point from housing
investment and minus 1.8 points from corporate capital spending.
</P>
<P>
External demand contributes plus 0.6 point, while government
outlays contribute plus 0.6 point.
</P>
<P>
The latest revision assumes no more collapses of major
financial institutions, no major global financial turmoil and an
exchange rate of 142 yen to one U.S. dollar, the average of the
past two months.
</P>
<P>
The EPA forecast personal consumption will slide an
inflation-adjusted 0.9 percent instead of the initially projected
2.5 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
The agency said corporate capital spending will likely shrink
an inflation-adjusted 10.1 percent, the biggest fall since fiscal
1993, when it dropped by 10.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The jobless rate in fiscal 1998 is projected to surge to 4.2
percent, a new record since the end of World War II. The jobless
rate was initially envisaged at 3.3 percent for the fiscal year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
