<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Says October War Paves Way for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 6 (Xinhua) -- On the 25th anniversary of the
1973 October War against Israel Tuesday, Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak termed the Egyptian victory in the war as a gateway to
peace.
</P>
<P>
"The October War was, undoubtedly, a bright mark in Egypt's
military history, it was not a war for the sake of war, but a war
to pave the path for peace," Mubarak said in an interview with
Good Morning Egypt television Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian army launched a surprise attack on October 6, 1973 and
crossed the Suez Canal into the Israeli-occupied Sinai
peninsular. Israel captured the peninsular in the 1967 Middle East
War.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptians were later pushed back, but the Arab hailed the
crossing as a victory that avenged the shame of the 1967 defeat.
</P>
<P>
Egyptians believe the rebuilding of Arab pride form the war led
to peace with Israel six years later, when Egypt signed the Camp
David peace accord with Israel, becoming the first Arab country to
make peace with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Egypt recovered all of its occupied Sinai lands in exchange for
living in peace with the northeastern neighbor while some Arab
lands still remain occupied by Israel, Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
But Mubarak used the war anniversary to criticize Israel in a
series of interviews, terming what he called Israel's growing
arsenal as a cause of concern in the Mideast, stressing the need
to render the region free of weapons of mass destruction and
maintain a balance of power.
</P>
<P>
"This is the greatest guarantee to peace in the region," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
