<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Daily to Accelerate Its Reform (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 6 (Xinhua ) -- As the official newspaper of
the Chinese Communist Party Central Committee, the People's Daily
will accelerate its reform, hoping to become more popular among
Chinese readers.
</P>
<P>
"In a time of heated media competition, the People's Daily must
become more reader-oriented, while maintaining its authority as a
Party newspaper," said the paper's president Shao Huaze here today.
</P>
<P>
He said that the People's Daily is expanding its retail network
nationwide, and readers will be able to buy it at newsstands in
all of China's major cities.
</P>
<P>
Shao said the paper will increase on-the-spot reporting,
focusing on timely information instead of the more boring
conference coverage.
</P>
<P>
The president also revealed that the paper will soon introduce
a new column monitoring government activities at different
levels. Also, the People's Daily's columns Theories Seminar and
Letters to the Editor will offer more space for reader discussions.
</P>
<P>
This year marks the 50th anniversary of the People's Daily,
which ranks sixth among the ten most influential newspapers
worldwide, according to a 1993 UNESCO evaluation.
</P>
<P>
The People's Daily has long been an authoritative newspaper in
the eyes of Chinese readers, having delved deeply into social
realities during the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, during the Cultural Revolution, the People's
Daily was manipulated by the "Gang of Four," a group of political
conspirators who used the paper as their propaganda tool.
</P>
<P>
The People's Daily played an important role in the 1980s,
calling for the redress of many cases mishandled during the
Cultural Revolution and clarifying several theoretic
controversies, thus regaining a steady rise in circulation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
