<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Daily to Accelerate Its Reform (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 6 (Xinhua ) -- The People's Daily has expanded
from 8 to 12 pages, with East China and South China editions, over
the last 5 years. The paper's newly launched electronic edition
attracts about 2 million visitors a day on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
"The Party's newspaper experts realize that the Party newspaper
might have a weakened influence on the people if it does not
follow the rules of mass communications," said Yu Guoming, deputy
director of the Public Opinion Research Institute of People's
University.
</P>
<P>
Fierce news competition is pushing the Chinese press,
including party newspapers, to advance industrialization,
noted Yu Youxian, director of the Press and Publications
Administration.
</P>
<P>
The number of Chinese newspapers has now reached more than
2,000, compared with about 100 in 1978, and the current
circulation of the People's Daily is about 3 million daily.
</P>
<P>
Currently, most of the People's Daily income comes from
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
Shao stressed that the paper is prepared to fair compete with
other news outlets such as the Xinhua News Agency and China
Central TV Station.
</P>
<P>
News reform is underway in China's mass media at all levels in
response to the market economy, and in the hope of attracting a
wider audience with a new and less formal style.
</P>
<P>
By 2010, Chinese newspapers will have formed some
conglomerates and some of these will join in the international
news competition, according to a Press and Publications
Administration plan.
</P>
<P>
Shao went on to say that the People's Daily as a party organ
will not fully depend on the market, because the paper's most
important characteristic is its incomparable authoritativeness.
</P>
<P>
After 20 years of reform and opening up, a versatile newspaper
network, with the party organ at the core, is coming into being in
China, and this will have a significant impact on the social
development of China in the 21st century, according to Yu Guoming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
