<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buddhist Monks in Famous Tibetan Temple Win Victory Over Rats (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Buddhists are taught not to kill
any living creature. Yet monks at the famed Jokhang Temple in the
Tibet Autonomous Region have waged a protracted crusade against
rats in the past four years that has resulted in annihilating
thousand upon thousand of rodents.
</P>
<P>
"Rats bite power lines, Tangkas (traditional Tibetan paintings)
and sutra scriptures," said Lhaba Lama who is in charge of
security work at the 1,300-year-old temple in Lhasa, the Tibetan
autonomous regional capital. "They drag Hada (silk ribbons) and
jump up and down among the oil lamps, often causing fires."
</P>
<P>
"The rodents even climbed onto the statue of Sakyamuni and bit
a hole into his face and took away one of his ears," said Kecu
Qingpa, 72, with obvious resentment." They gnaw bits of gold from
the statues and carry them to caves."
</P>
<P>
The Jokhang Temple was first built by Songtsan Gambo, the
chieftain of the Tubo Dynasty, when he married Princess Wencheng
of the Tang Dynasty in the year 641. The holy statue of Sakyamuni
was said to be brought by the princess from Chang'an, capital of
the Tang Dynasty. It is now under first-class state protection for
cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
The widely held religious belief in Tibet of not killing any
living thing turned Lhasa into a paradise for pests like rats and
flies, and rich and sumptuous tributes in the temples attracted
and fed a large number of rats,
</P>
<P>
The rodents were often seen strolling in temples during the day
or walking side by side playfully with monks in the middle of
rituals and ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
When residents in Lhasa were aroused to wipe out rats in the
early 1990's, the creatures took shelter in temples in growing
numbers, and their annoying presence finally made the monks
resolved to get rid of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Banks Tighten Control of Foreign Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese banks have as of
Tuesday bought foreign currencies on "managing and keeping"
accounts of economic organizations that are supposed to sell
foreign currencies to banks in case the latter do not obey the
obligation, Vietnam News Agency said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This measure, aimed at tightening the control of foreign
currencies, was taken in line with a government decision on
economic organizations' obligations to sell and their right to buy
foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
Under the decision, the economic organizations have been
allowed to use current outstanding balances in their accounts for
the settlement of due transactions.
</P>
<P>
If their outstanding balances are not sufficient for
transactions, they are permitted to pay for the rest by available
foreign currencies in their "managing and keeping" accounts.
</P>
<P>
They are entitled to sell foreign currencies in "managing and
keeping" accounts to other banks after submitting signed foreign
currency trading contracts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
