<HEADLINE> Buddhist Monks in Famous Tibetan Temple Win Victory Over Rats (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Buddhists are taught not to kill
any living creature. Yet monks at the famed Jokhang Temple in the
Tibet Autonomous Region have waged a protracted crusade against
rats in the past four years that has resulted in the deaths of
over 1,000 rodents.
</P>
<P>
"Rats bite power lines, Tangkas (Tibetan paintings) and sutra
scriptures," said Lhaba Lama who is in charge of security work at
the 1,300-year-old temple in Lhasa, the Tibetan autonomous
regional capital. "They drag Hada (silk ribbons) and jump up and
down among the oil lamps, often causing fires."
</P>
<P>
"The rodents even climbed onto the statue of Sakyamuni and bit
a hole into his face and took away one of his ears," said Kecu
Qingpa, 72, with obvious resentment." They gnaw bits of gold from
the statues and carry them to caves."
</P>
<P>
The Jokhang Temple was first built by Songtsan Gambo, the
chieftain of the Tubo Dynasty, when he married Princess Wencheng
of the Tang Dynasty in the year 641. The holy statue of Sakyamuni
was said to be brought by the princess from Chang'an, capital of
the Tang Dynasty. It is now under first-class state protection for
cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
The widely held religious belief in Tibet of not killing any
living thing turned Lhasa into a paradise for pests like rats and
flies, and rich and sumptuous tributes in the temples attracted
and fed a large number of rats,
</P>
<P>
The rodents were often seen strolling in temples during the day
or walking side by side playfully with monks in the middle of
rituals and ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
When residents in Lhasa were aroused to wipe out rats in the
early 1990's, the creatures took shelter in temples in growing
numbers, and their annoying presence finally made the monks
resolved to get rid of them.
