</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buddhist Monks in Famous Tibetan Temple Win Victory Over Rats (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At first, monks at the Jokhang Temple did not kill the rats,
but simply caught them by placing meat in large and deep boxes and
then set them free outside the temple.
</P>
<P>
However, this method proved futile, said Lhaba Lama. The rats
would return soon after and continue to make trouble, eating
tributes and damaging Buddhist statues.
</P>
<P>
"We had to take their lives since they kept harming the
temple," said Dainba Cuse, deputy director of the Temple
administration committee.
</P>
<P>
A consensus was soon reached and rat poison was spread in
places most frequented by the rodents. More than 1,000 rats were
killed in 1995 alone, the first year of the four-year campaign.
</P>
<P>
The dead rats were put into sandbags, and before burying them
the monks chanted sutras, praying they would not be born as rats
in their next lives.
</P>
<P>
The monks finally won a victory over the rats -- only six or
seven were found poisoned in the temple this year.
</P>
<P>
"Killing rats does not directly contradict our doctrine of not
killing any living creatures," said Kecu Qingpa. "We are doing the
killing for the sake of our temple and in the interest of thousand
upon thousand of our followers or worshippers, as well as for the
protection of invaluable cultural relics."
</P>
<P>
"Killing rats should be on no account regarded as a big sin,"
said the old lama. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
