<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Road Construction Investment to Reach One-Billion Yuan Daily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 6 (Xinhua) -- China will invest one-billion
yuan (120.48 million U.S. dollars) per day on average to build
highways in the remaining months of this year, the Ministry of
Communications has announced.
</P>
<P>
The 180-billion-yuan (21.69 billion U.S. dollars) target for
1998 road construction is only half complete, and the pace of
highway-building must be speeded up, an official said.
</P>
<P>
The last quarter of this year will see a historic peak for
highway construction in China, as the country is set to add 33,000
kilometers of highways in 1998, including 1,560 kilometers of
expressways and 7,947 kilometers of high-grade roads, all
historic highs.
</P>
<P>
The State Council, China's highest governing body,
recently added another 20 billion yuan (2.41 billion U.S. dollars) to
road construction investment, which had already risen to 160
billion yuan (19.28 billion U.S. dollars) from the initial figure
of 120 billion yuan (14.46 billion U.S. dollars) early this year.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Communications has called for consolidated
efforts to build major national highways, upgrade road networks,
improve rural road conditions, repair flood-ravaged roads in the
valleys of the Yangtze, Nenjiang, and Songhua rivers, and
begin the construction of 20-billion-yuan (2.41 billion
U.S. dollars) worth of new projects.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has vowed to ensure high-quality road
construction in spite of the arduous task.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Cracks Down on Illegal Foreign Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam launched a crackdown on
illegal and unqualified foreign workers last week, the latest
issue of the newspaper Vietnam Investment Review reported.
</P>
<P>
The move was part of a comprehensive initiative to rid the
country of thousands of unwanted guests, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners working in Vietnam must possess valid professional
degrees and certificates and working permits according to a recent
stipulation by the Ministry of Labor, War Invalids and Social
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Illegal foreign workers will be deported and unqualified
foreign workers also face deportation if their employment papers
do not meet the requirements.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners working in Vietnam for a period of three months or
more within a year must possess working permits as stipulated by
the Vietnamese government.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey of Vietnam's relevant departments showed that
about 7,000 foreigners are currently working in Vietnam, but the
majority of them do not hold professional degrees or certificates.
</P>
<P>
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Calls for Unified EU Policy on Immigration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini Tuesday called for a unified European Union (EU) policy on
aid to countries often as origins of illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
Addressing in Luxembourg a meeting of EU foreign ministers,
Dini urged the regional bloc's 15 member states to work out a
joint response to the swelling tide of immigrants.
</P>
<P>
"At least a part of the development aid should be directed
towards projects which can help limit the flow of immigration
across the Mediterranean," he said.
</P>
<P>
Preferential treatment should be granted to the countries who
"have shown a greater awareness of the importance of regulating
the phenomenon," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The EU should also consider "specific support for countries
most affected by the need to protect the union's external
borders," Dini said, short of giving details whether the support
in his mind was of finance or of any other nature.
</P>
<P>
He said determined, joint action by the 15 members was as
important for the immigrants themselves as it was for the EU.
</P>
<P>
Dini also gave a report on Italy's extensive efforts over the
last year to stem the influx of immigrants into Europe via its
long coastline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
