<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Envoy Arrives on Thursday to Reduce Iran-Afghan Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Secretary General's
Special Envoy on Afghanistan Lakhdar Brahimi arrives here Thursday
on the second leg of his visit to the region to try to reduce
prevailing tension between Afghanistan and Iran.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi will hold talks with Pakistani officials on Friday.
During his week-long stay here, he is also scheduled to meet Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif and Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz, the
Associated Press of Pakistan reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The visit is aimed at further strengthening the U.N. efforts
towards a peaceful settlement of the conflict in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The decision to send Brahimi to the region after the Six Plus
Two (Afghanistan's six immediate neighbors plus the U.S. and
Russia) meeting held in New York last week called for renewed U.N.
efforts to broker peace in the war-ravaged country.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, Iran, Turkmenistan, Tajikistan, Uzbekistan, China,
Russia and the U.S. agreed at the meeting that the U.N. should
send its representatives to address the Afghan conflict in a
peaceful manner.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi, who has also been to the region earlier as part of his
mission to restore peace in the conflict-torn country, comes at a
time when Tehran has threatened to take military action against
the ruling Taliban.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban now control over 95 percent of Afghanistan and the
international community has called for a broad-based government in
Kabul.  
</P>
</TEXT>
