<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Sets Deadline for Illegal Foreign Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Foreign workers without valid
permits in Jordan have been given two weeks to one month's time to
correct their status, or to leave.
</P>
<P>
The country's on-going campaign to regulate the foreign labor
market since last Wednesday target those "who entered the country
as visitors or tourists but remain in the country for work," the
semi-official Jordan Times Tuesday quoted Minister of Information
Nasir Judeh as saying.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Interior Nayef Al Qadi said the Iraqis will be
accorded special treatment in the campaign for a humane point of
view because of the difficult situation in their country.
</P>
<P>
Qadi added that the government is determined to regulate the
foreign labor market, because there are "frightening numbers" of
foreigners in the kingdom who add to the current economic
difficulties and increase the unemployment rate among the
Jordanians to some 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
Up to 1 million foreigners now stay in Jordan, the bulk of whom
are Egyptians, Syrians and Iraqis, said Qadi.
</P>
<P>
Only 62,000 of them have residence permits and work permits
and many more are working illegally, he added.
</P>
<P>
Police have rounded up hundreds of Asian workers to check their
status during the campaign.
</P>
<P>
Similar actions on the Arab workers in Jordan will be carried
out later.
</P>
<P>
The non-Jordanian workers are easy to find jobs as employers
often pay them low wages and do not have to undertake their
insurance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
