<HEADLINE> Horticulture Earns Zambia $40M in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Zambia exported 5,500 tons of
horticultural products in 1997, earning for the country 40
million U.S. Dollars, according to the Zambia Export Growers
Association (ZEGA).
</P>
<P>
The weekly Financial Mail published Tuesday quoted ZEGA Chief
Executive Mable Mandela as saying recently that "This year, the
volume of exports is expected to rise further as acreage has
expanded by over 30 percent for the current 1998/1999 export
season."
</P>
<P>
"So we are talking about 52 million Dollars which translates
to 104 billion Kwacha," she said.
</P>
<P>
The sector is also a provider of employment to approximately
800 Zambians in the season.
</P>
<P>
The association together with eight other horticultural trade
associations from five African countries agreed last month to
constitute a steering committee with a view to harmonizing trade
codes in the region and ultimately opening more export doors for
the sub-continent. 
</P>
