<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10,000 People Surf Internet In Hainan Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, October 6 ( Xinhua ) -- Some 10,000 people are
now surfing the Internet in Hainan Province, accounting for 0.14
percent of the province's population, a proportion higher than
the country's average.
</P>
<P>
Considering that 80 percent of the province's people are rural
residents, and that some 5 or 6 years ago, local people had to
stand in line to make long-distance phone calls, their access to
the Internet now is incredible, said a local government official.
</P>
<P>
Haikou, the provincial capital of Hainan Province, opened its
first Chinanet port in 1996, and now has 19 cities and counties
with Internet access. Users all over the province are now able to
get online through local direct-dialing networks.
</P>
<P>
Internet fans in the province have established clubs
which is drawing the attention of people from all walks of life,
including the vice-president of the province Wang Houhong, who is
said to be an Internet fan.
</P>
<P>
Local sources said that public information, tourism and
agricultural information websites are all under construction.
</P>
<P>
Since last year, local economic departments have been
displaying their investment projects on the Internet, while the
government has also been publishing official statistics and
information regularly on the 'Net.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 08:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria to Allow Army Commander to Run for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Syria, a power broker in Lebanon,
has thrown its weight behind Lebanese army commander Emile Lahoud
as Lebanon's next president.
</P>
<P>
At a marathon eight-hour summit in Damascus on Monday, Syrian
President Hafez al-Assad and his Lebanese counterpart Elias Hrawi
agreed to amend the third clause of Article 49 of the Lebanese
constitution to allow the army commander to formally run for the
post, the Daily Star reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The clause stipulates that the country's first-rank civil
servants wishing to stand in a presidential election should quit
their current posts two years in advance of the vote.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz, the outgoing president's
son-in-law has publicly confirmed the scenario which was leaked to
the press shortly after Hrawi's return to Beirut.
</P>
<P>
"The president will propose very soon an amendment of Article
49 involving only the clause that bans first-rank civil servant,"
Boueiz told reporters after meeting with Hrawi.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the 68-year-old incumbent president, who will
end his nine-year term by October 24, is expected to propose the
amendment at the next cabinet meeting scheduled for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet will endorse the proposal and then refer to the
parliament which, if it ratifys the bill, will vote for the
country's 11th president since its independence in 1943.
</P>
<P>
Syria, with 35,000 troops deployed in Lebanon as peacekeepers,
is regarded as the king-maker in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud, 62, a close ally of Syria, was appointed as the
country's army commander in November, 1989, on the eve of the end
of the country's 15-year-old sectarian civil war.
</P>
<P>
He has gained popular support from Lebanese, including most of
politicians, due to his landmark achievements in rebuilding the
country's army into a cohesive fighting machine after its tragic
disintegration during the civil war.
</P>
<P>
Many people believe that he is a reform-minded leader and will
introduce drastic changes into political life which is described
by the country's opposition as full of corruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Banks Assets Shoot Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Combined resources of banks in
the Philippines reached 2.84 trillion pesos (71 billion U.S.
dollars) in the first half of this year, outpacing the whole 1997
record of 2.82 trillion pesos (70.5 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Data released Tuesday by the central bank showed that the
increase in the assets was due to the rise in the number of
commercial bank branches in the country.
</P>
<P>
The data showed that the commercial banks' branches rose from
3,411 in December 31, 1997 to 3,491 in the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the number of commercial banks grew to a total of
41, contrary to central bank governor Gabriel Singson's earlier
statement that there were 54 commercial banks, including 14
foreign bank branches in the country.
</P>
<P>
Deeply concerned about the overcrowding of local branches, the
central bank has frozen new applications for opening branches in
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0191 </DOCNO>
