<HEADLINE> Jordan Urges Syria-Turkey Dialog Over Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Fayez
Tarawneh has urged Turkey and Syria to exercise restraint and
settle their disputes by peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
Continuous dialog is the only way for them to defuse their
tension, Tarawneh said upon his return from the United States late
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
"There is time to discuss the root of all problems" and the
crisis is expected to be over soon, he said.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, Jordan will spare no efforts to help them
conduct dialog and maintain stability and security of the whole
region, Tarawneh said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's military officials said last week that their country
is in a state of undeclared war with Syria due to Damascus'
alleged support for Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long accused Syria of sheltering PKK rebels, which
have been fighting since 1984 for autonomy for the Kurdish
minority in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Syria denied the charges, but accused Turkey of forming
military alliance with Israel that threaten Arab security and
undermine Syria's bargaining position in peace talks with the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Tensions built up after Turkey massed troops along the Syrian
border to conduct military exercises. Turkey claimed that it is
ready to use force against Syria if diplomacy fails.
</P>
<P>
It is widely deemed that Jordan is facing difficult situation
on this issue because it enjoys close military and political ties
with Turkey while having strained relations with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Syria, one of the Arab states that have territorial disputes
with Israel, opposes Jordan's making peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Jordan are the only two Arab countries that signed
peace treaties with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Federal Assembly Adopts Resolution on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Federal Assembly of the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia Monday adopted a resolution on the
Kosovo issue, saying it backed the government's related position.
</P>
<P>
The resolution attributed the Kosovo crisis to the separatist
motives of the Kosovo ethnic Albanians, who want to break away
from the Yugoslav Federation, Tanjug news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav armed forces have taken measures of "needed depth and
scope" to curb "criminal activities" of the ethnic Albanians and
"terrorist gangs" in Kosovo, the resolution said, giving full
affirmation of the efforts in this regard by the Yugoslav armed
forces and Serbia's Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The assembly strongly condemned countries which offered "Kosovo
Albanian gangs" training bases, money and weapons, and criticized
Albania by name for doing so.
</P>
<P>
The assembly noted that the Yugoslav Federation has halted
activities in Kosovo, pulling its troops back to their base, and
opening all parts of Kosovo to humanitarian groups, journalists
and diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Such measures have created conditions necessary for dialogue
with Kosovo Albanian leaders, the assembly said, adding it has
fully met the requirements under the U.N. Security Council
resolution on the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
The assembly supported the Federal government's stand on the
Kosovo issue and called on the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) to make a fact-finding trip to the
troubled Serbian province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Take Action Against Garment Quota Manipulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government will
take stern action against garment quota manipulation in a bid to
achieve export target despite the devastating floods, media
reports here said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The action will be taken against the backdrop that certain
dishonest people are manipulating the quota to the United States
and the GSP (Generalized System of Preferences) in the European
Union, the reports quoted sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The garment export target of 5.83 billion U.S. dollars for the
July 1998-June 1999 fiscal year could be exceeded if some
pragmatic steps are taken, Commerce and Industries Minister Tofael
Ahmed observed at a high-level meeting Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the fifth Five-Year Plan, the garment export for 1998-99
was originally set at 5.63 billion dollars, and it was re-fixed
upward after some non-traditional items were included in the
export list.
</P>
<P>
The government will closely monitor the entire system to check
manipulation and protect the interests of the real exporters,
Ahmed told the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The garment sector, which has been growing at an annual rate of
over 20 percent over the past few years, is the country's largest
foreign exchange earner.
</P>
<P>
There are about 2,500 garment factories in the country with
around 1.3 million workers in the sector. Exports of garments
stood 2.845 billion U.S. dollars, accounting for 55.09 percent of
the total export earnings of 5.16 billion dollars in the previous
fiscal year ending on June 30, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
