<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia's First Test-Tube Triplets Thriving in Guizhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Asia's first test-tube triplets
are growing up healthily in China's southwestern Guizhou Province
as they begin their education at a local kindergarten this fall.
</P>
<P>
The three test-tube girls, named Zhang Jingjing, Zhang Xinxin
and Zhang Sensen, were born in a Beijing hospital on January 30,
1995. Their father and mother belong to China's ancient ethnic
Gelo and Tujia groups.
</P>
<P>
Their parents had no child seven years after their marriage,
and their mother, Tang Huixian, became infertile after an
operation excising her tubal fimbria because of three ectopic
pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
With the help of professor Zhang Lizhu, considered the mother
of China's test-tube babies, Tang managed to give birth to her
test-tube triplets.
</P>
<P>
Their parents said the three sisters have all been healthy and
have seldom needed to go to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
The triplets have different characteristics, but all three have
IQs higher than those of most children their age. They could recite
ancient poems of the Tang Dynasty (618-907) when they were only 18
months old, their parents said, adding that now they can recite 15
popular Tang Dynasty poems.
</P>
<P>
Since the first test-tube baby was born in 1978 in Britain, the
world has seen some 200,000 test-tube children, over 500 in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0197 </DOCNO>
