<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Israeli Soldiers Killed in Southern Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Two Israeli soldiers were
killed and six others wounded in a roadside bomb attack by
Hezbollah guerillas in southern Lebanon Monday afternoon, Israel
Radio reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A number of bombs were detonated one after another as a convoy
of four Israeli military vehicles were driving in the eastern
sector of the so-called "security zone," the reports said. Two
vehicles were hit in the explosions, apparently detonated by
remote control.
</P>
<P>
The deaths have brought to 14 the number of the Israelis who
were killed in southern Lebanon since the beginning of the
year. Dozens have been wounded.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, whose guerrillas are fighting to oust Israeli
troops from a 1,200-kilometer border zone set up by Israel in
southern Lebanon in 1985, has claimed responsibility for the
attack Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army has been looking for ways to deal with the
renewed use of roadside bombs by Hezbollah guerillas in the
security zone. In late August, three Israelis -- two soldiers and
one civilian working for the army -- were killed by bombs in less
than 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
Israel is seeking to withdraw from southern Lebanon on
condition that the Lebanese government makes necessary security
arrangement, but Lebanon and its main ally Syria have rejected
the Israeli offer, insisting that the U.N. Resolution 425 calls
for "unconditional withdrawal." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Star Shining Over Oasis in Northwestern Xinjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-seven-year-old Erna Grimm
of Switzerland never imagined that teaching English at the Hotan
Oasis in the Taklimakan Desert would make her so popular among the
local Uygur people.
</P>
<P>
"We all know the foreigner. She is a star here. Many people
are following her to learn English, and she can speak Uygur
well, too," a taxi driver told a Xinhua reporter on the way to
Erna's home.
</P>
<P>
Erna is now the only foreigner at the Hotan Oasis on the
ancient Silk Road through the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, as
a wave of English-learning sweeps over the oasis.
</P>
<P>
The oasis is considered one of the poorest areas in China, and
has long been isolated from the modern information society. Nearly
98 percent of the local residents are Uygurs.
</P>
<P>
Erna now teaches English at a local teacher-training school,
the highest academic institution in the locality. She can speak
and teach in Uygur. However Erna can be easily distinguished from
local women because of her blonde hair and foreign accent.
</P>
<P>
Erna was granted bachelor's degree in the Uygur language in
1994 after five years of study at a teacher-training college in
Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
She went back to Switzerland after graduation, but returned to
Xinjiang in 1996 after a year back home. She then started teaching
English at her present school, where she conducts 17 lessons a
week.
</P>
<P>
In her spare time, many people gather at her house to learn
English, including civil servants, middle-school students, nurses,
businesspeople and even housewives.
</P>
<P>
"I learned Arabic before coming to China, so I planned to work
in an Arab country after graduation. But considering the low
social status of Arabian women, I changed my mind," Erna said.
</P>
<P>
Erna came to Xinjiang in 1989, where the Uygur language has
existed for thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
In her eyes, the once-isolated oasis is changing due to the
country's market-oriented economic reform and opening-up. In
recent years, more and more overseas tourists are flooding into
the oasis, a "lonely island in the desert."
</P>
<P>
On both sides of the local streets advertising signs with
English words can been seen occasionally, along with Chinese and
Uygur characters.
</P>
<P>
Erna was given a beautiful Uygur name, Ayinur, which means
"moonlight." She is now teaching herself Chinese, and is
able to speak a little with her Chinese neighbors.
</P>
<P>
She expressed the hope that what she will help the local
farmers appreciate the importance of schooling for their children.
</P>
<P>
"I think that the day will come when local people overcome the
desert and shirk off poverty, and they will become well off soon,"
Erna said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
