<HEADLINE> Chinese Provincial Silk Producers Threatened By Restaurant Patrons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Shandong Province, one of
China's leading silk producers, is faced with diminishing silk
output because the silkworm chrysalis is being favored by more
and more local eaters.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Morning Post today blamed this newly developed
taste for silkworms in the coastal province as one of the reasons
for its declining silk trade.
</P>
<P>
Shandong used to be known as one of the top three silk
producers in China, but since the beginning of the 1980s more and
more locals, benefiting from the economic boom, have begun to
demand the flavor of silkworms, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
Currently, restaurateurs are paying 14 yuan for one kilo
of silkworm cocoons, while silk companies pay only six to eight
yuan a kilo, said the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
