<HEADLINE> Heilongjiang Repairs Damaged Water-Control Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Heilongjiang
Province has pledged to complete during the winter-spring period
the repair of all water-control projects destroyed by torrential
rains and summer flooding.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has mobilized 3 million people to drain
water from farmlands, dig silt, and rebuild damaged water-control
projects. Leading officials at all levels have gone to the
construction sites to organize this province-wide campaign.
</P>
<P>
According to local authorities, floods washed out 637 levee
sections with a total length of 1,988 kilometers, 124 large and
medium-sized reservoirs, and 45,300 pumping wells, causing direct
economic losses estimated at 2.4 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Taiyang Island, a noted scenic spot in the provincial capital
of Harbin, reopened recently following renovation after being
inundated by floods for two months and suffering economic losses
of 3.5 billion yuan to Harbin.
</P>
<P>
The city plans to offset its losses by holding an ice festival,
campfire parties and kite competitions, and opening new tourist
sites.  
</P>
</TEXT>
