<HEADLINE> Jordan: Progress of Peace Process Expected Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 6 (Xinhua) -- United States Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright's visit to the region is expected to bring
tangible progress to the long-stalled Palestinian-Israeli peace
talks, said Jordanian Prime Minister Fayez Tarawneh here late
Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
"It is expected that the mission will be followed by meetings
between the two sides (the Palestinians and Israel) in Washington
during this month to finalize an agreement and start serious work
for negotiating the final status (issues)," said the prime
minister upon his return from the U.S..
</P>
<P>
There are great expectations that the agreement about Israeli
troops withdrawal from the occupied West Bank will be achieved
between the Palestinians and Israel in the coming days, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there is a sense of optimism that things have
reached "a mature stage" not only on the Israeli troops
withdrawal, but on a host of other issues, he said, while not
elaborating in details.
</P>
<P>
In this sense, Albright's visit will "put the peace process in
a better framework," he added.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister started his visit to the U.S. last Friday
and later met Albright and King Hussein, who is there to treat his
cancer.
</P>
<P>
His meetings with the two leaders focused on the latest
developments of the peace process on the Palestinian-Israeli
track, said Tarawneh.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace negotiations have been deadlocked
since March last year, due to the Jewish settlement expansion in
Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. earlier this year put forward a proposal, which calls
for Israel to withdraw from 13.1 percent of the occupied West
Bank. The current mediation efforts have been focusing on the
proposal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
