<HEADLINE> China's Largest Cotton Producer Lowers Purchasing Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, the nation's major cotton producer, recently
lowered cotton prices in response to slack domestic and foreign
demand.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang, which currently produces 25 percent of China's cotton
output, has suffered from sluggish cotton sales due to oversupply
on the market in recent years.
</P>
<P>
This year's cotton output is projected at 1.2 million tons,
up substantially due a 10 percent increase in land dedicated to
cotton.
</P>
<P>
The local government cut cotton prices by 10 percent on 1997
levels and has adopted various other measures to increase cotton
sales. The Agricultural Development Bank also granted credit loans
totalling 5.5 billion yuan (660 million dollars) to facilitate
cotton purchases.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Xinjiang Regional Agriculture Department
plan to develop improved cotton varieties to enhance the region's
market competitiveness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
