<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Terms Syria Center of Terrorism in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz has said that Syria is the center of terrorism in the
Middle East and it shelters all the terrorists.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the Turkish private Star TV late Monday night,
Yilmaz said that Syria is the country that not only shelters the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), but also many other
terrorist organizations.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long accused Syria of harboring the PKK, who has
been fighting since 1984 for autonomy for the Kurdish minority in
southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The PKK frequently wages cross-border raids on Turkey from its
camps in Iraq, Iran and Syria, local officials said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, which sent 10,000 troops late last week into northern
Iraq to wipe out the Kurdish bases there, has threatened to use
force to destroy the Kurdish bases within Syrian borders.
</P>
<P>
It has also recently massed heavy troops along the border with
Syria to conduct military exercises, which fueled the tensions
between the neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz, asking Syria to extradite the heads of the PKK
organization for trial, said that since 1980s, Syria has
sheltered PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan and provided training camps
on its territory.
</P>
<P>
Syria, which has denied the charges, accused Turkey, in return,
of forming military alliance with Israel to target against the
Arab world, especially Syria, and betray the interests of the
Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, a predominantly Muslim but politically secular country,
has been criticized by many of the Arab states for forming a
military alliance with Israel, which is regarded as a threat the
regional security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
