<HEADLINE> Key Water Control Project Progresses Smoothly in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Work on the Manlha Water Control
Project, the largest key water conservancy project in soutwest
China's Tibet Autonomous Region, is progressing smoothly.
</P>
<P>
The project will be completed at an estimated cost of one
billion yuan (120 million U.S. dollars) in five years, according
to local officials.
</P>
<P>
Manlha is located in Gyaze County in southwestern Xigaze
Prefecture. The facility will contribute not only to irrigation
and power generation, but also to flood control and the tourism
industry in the region.
</P>
<P>
The large project will includes construction of a dam, flood
water discharge tunnels and a power station, with the reservoir's
total storage capacity hitting 155 million cu.m. The power
station, with an installed generating capacity of 20,000 kw, is
expected to generate 61 million kwh of electricity a year. The
project will provide irrigation for 16,000 hectares of farmland.
</P>
<P>
Officials note that the project will not only provide
irrigation for farmland, grasslands and forests in comparatively
developed areas in the lower reaches of the Nyangqu River, but
will also solve problems related shortages of energy and potable
water.
</P>
<P>
Construction work on the main part of the project commenced in
August 1995 and will be completed within a five-year period.
</P>
</TEXT>
