<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Who Reads Literature Today? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey reveals that
young people with higher educations but low salaries comprise the
majority of readers of literary works, according to today's
Shanghai-based Wenhui Daily.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted by People's Literature, one of the
country's leading literary magazines.
</P>
<P>
The result shows that 56 percent of these readers are between
16 and 29 years of age, and most have higher degrees or have
completed high school.
</P>
<P>
The majority are salary earners whose monthly incomes is below
700 yuan (about 84 U.S. dollars). They seem to have more spare
time than businesspeople, but they lack the money to buy all the
books they would like.
</P>
<P>
When asked why they like works of literature, 82 percent of the
respondents said they believe good literary works are artistic
treats, while another 14.7 percent expressed the wish to follow
topics of general interest by reading novels.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that novels describing the bitterness and
happiness of common people in their daily lives are most popular
among readers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
