<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afforestation Project Reduces Dust Levels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A major ongoing afforestation
project has significantly reduced wind and dust levels in Beijing
and Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics for Beijing, the Chinese capital, show that
the 16.5 tons of dust deposited per kilometer during 1997
represented a drop of 4.5 tons on the 1986 level.
</P>
<P>
Today's People's Daily (overseas edition) reported that Beijing
has experienced an average of only 3.8 dusty days annually since
the mid-1990s, down dramatically from 20.5 days in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Silt accumulating in the Miyun Reservoir, the capital's
main source of water located in northeastern part of the city, has
dropped by 60 percent on levels common in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
The afforestation project, approved by the State Council in
1986, calls for planting trees and sowing grass over 3.73 million
hectares around Beijing and Tianjin by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Related projects were completed on 1.87 million hectares in
1997, according to the State Administration of Forestry.
</P>
<P>
A Xinhua News Agency story released in late 1970s described
Beijing as a windy and dusty "gray and yellow" city. "The sky in
the middle of the day is often as dark as at dusk," said the
story, adding that "strong winds and blowing dust often prevent
people from opening their eyes."
</P>
<P>
Experts affirmed the notable achievements of the afforestation
project. However, they stressed that the Beijing and Tianjin area
has a fragile ecosystem and called for greater afforestation
efforts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
