<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Henan Expands Power Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Generating units with a total
installed capacity of close to 2.08 million kw will go on stream
this year in central China's Henan Province to fuel the current
efforts on the fulfillment of the province's nine-percent economic
growth target for 1998.
</P>
<P>
Investments in medium-sized and large power projects during
1998 will exceed four billion yuan, according to the provincial
electrical power company.
</P>
<P>
Henan, which leads other provinces in terms of population, has
a total generating capacity of over 10 million kw. However, the
province's annual per capita power consumption of only 710 kwh
falls far below the national average.
</P>
<P>
Power shortage continues to affect over five million people in
the province and great efforts are needed to develop the power
industry in rural areas, a company executive said.
</P>
<P>
The province added 4.21 million kw. to its generating capacity
between 1990-1995, with the total capacity hitting 10.07 million
kw at the end of 1995. Another one million kw was added to
generating units by the end July this year, helping lay a solid
foundation for fulfilling the year's target of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, Henan's total power industry
investment for the period between 1996-2000 will hit than 77
billion yuan, with the total generating capacity expected to grow
by five million kw.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
