<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Painter Wants Every Country To Know Him </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese painter plans to have
the whole world become familiar with his work in several years.
</P>
<P>
Xu Dongdong, 39, announced here today that he will donate an
album of his paintings to every major library and museum
throughout the world to help eliminate Western indifference to
Chinese art.
</P>
<P>
"Some thousands of years ago China developed its fine arts,
which are unique and superb. But the world still does not fully
appreciate its beauty," he said.
</P>
<P>
Liu, well-versed in Chinese traditional and water-ink painting,
has been awarded the title of the First Grade Painter of the State.
</P>
<P>
He said that European and American works occupy the most
eye-catching places in museums, while Chinese works are usually
displayed in the corners.
</P>
<P>
Xu has spent his savings printing the albums of his work, and
has already donated them to the top 500 libraries in the world,
some of which have accepted his paintings.
</P>
<P>
Xu has received support from the Chinese government for this
effort. "What Xu is doing is of great significance, and these
international cultural exchanges will help the world understand
China better," said Sun Jiazheng, China's cultural minister.
</P>
<P>
Xu's plan has already aroused public attention.
</P>
<P>
"He is one of a few painters who are taking actions to
challenge the dignity of Western academia, and this reflects the
fact that with the growth of the Chinese economy, more people are
hoping that Chinese culture will be appreciated by the
world," said Chen Wei, a researcher at the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
