<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Vows to End Capital Controls With Condition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Tuesday committed
itself to ending capital controls on condition that greater
discipline is enforced on the international currency market.
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to ending capital controls, but only if the
world financial community instills greater discipline into the
international currency market," Malaysian Special Functions
Minister Tun Daim Zainuddin said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has introduced capital control "as a means of
insulating ourselves from the chaotic international currency
markets and predatory speculators," Daim, who is also the
executive director of the National Economic Action Council (NEAC),
said at the opening of the National Congress on Economic Recovery:
The Way Forward" here.
</P>
<P>
But the regime of controls that Malaysia has adopted is
"selective" and "The exchange control measures do not hinder
long-term foreign investment in the economy, it is the movement of
massive short-term capital that we seek to control," Daim said.
</P>
<P>
"Our capital control measures may be controversial and could
have negative implications in our sovereign profile, but lower
credit rating must surely be less damaging to the economy than the
risk of tailspin effects from a high interest rates strategy," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Defending the measures, Daim said Malaysia's attempt to control
capital flows has surely stirred international debate and world
opinion now "favors a new financial architecture to govern capital
flows."
</P>
<P>
He said the selected exchange controls introduced to insulate
the domestic economy from the global financial crisis provided the
economy some breathing room to recover.
</P>
<P>
They allowed the government to ease interest rates and raise
domestic demand without destabilizing the ringgit, the country's
currency, further, he said, adding, "Foreign exchange stability is
crucial for us to implement the other policy reforms including
bank and corporate restructuring."
</P>
<P>
The new exchange rate of 3.8 ringgit to the U.S. dollar lowers
the cost of imported capital goods by nearly 10 percent and it
also reduces the cost of servicing foreign debt not only for the
government but also for the private sector, Daim said.
</P>
<P>
Daim noted that more experts were saying Malaysia did the right
thing in introducing new exchange control and economic measures
recently to defend the ringgit against speculation and stimulate
the economy.
</P>
<P>
He said that ensuring sufficient liquidity in the economy forms
a crucial piece of the government's policy package for recovery.
</P>
<P>
For the economic recovery, Daim said, Malaysia needs some 60
billion ringgit (15.879 billion U.S. dollars) between now and the
year 2000 to finance economic recovery plan recommendations.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that the amount is too much for the federal
government to bear alone and thus a variety of funding sources
have been identified, mostly local institutions.
</P>
<P>
Daim expressed his confidence that although the current slow
growth is expected to prevail until next year given the continued
sluggishness in the region, Malaysia's economy would recover in
early 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Leaders Call for a Curb on Economic Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Financial leaders from 26
economies Monday called for currency support, financial and
corporate reforms to prevent a global recession caused by a
worsening world financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
At a special meeting, finance ministers and central bank
governors from the Group of Seven most industrialized nations
(G-7) and emerging market economies discussed the current
financial crisis and its impact on the global financial system.
</P>
<P>
They underscored the need for ongoing, urgent efforts to
address the difficulties faced by a number of economies and to
stem further deterioration.
</P>
<P>
"They called for a particular focus on support for the
vulnerable groups in society and for ways to address more
forcefully financial and corporate restructuring," said a
Chairmen's Statement after the meeting Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The statement said financial leaders recognized that intensive
work was underway on these matters in various countries and their
appropriate international financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The ministers and governors emphasized that sound domestic
policies are fundamental to healthy and robust national economies
and financial sectors, and equally important to the world economy.
</P>
<P>
The financial officials urged the International Monetary Fund,
the World Bank and other relevant organizations to consider
strengthening the international financial structure.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to give more attention to promoting soundly based
flow of capital, further improvements in transparency and
disclosure, strengthening financial systems, maintaining
sustainable exchange rates, and developing new ways to prevent and
respond to crises.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton addressed the opening session of
the meeting and called for a strengthened world financial
architecture to halt the financial crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
