<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Federal Assembly Adopts Resolution on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Federal Assembly of the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia Monday adopted a resolution on the
Kosovo issue, saying it backed the government's related position.
</P>
<P>
The resolution attributed the Kosovo crisis to the separatist
motives of the Kosovo ethnic Albanians, who want Serbia to break
away from the Yugoslav Federation, Tanjug news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav armed forces have taken measures of "needed depth and
scope" to curb "criminal activities" of the ethnic Albanians and
"terrorist gangs" in Kosovo, the resolution said, giving full
affirmation of the efforts in this regard by the Yugoslav armed
forces and Serbia's Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The assembly strongly condemned countries which offered "Kosovo
Albanian gangs" training bases, money and weapons, and criticized
Albania by name for doing so.
</P>
<P>
The assembly noted that the Yugoslav Federation has halted
activities in Kosovo, pulling its troops back to their bases, and
opening all parts of Kosovo to humanitarian groups, journalists
and diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Such measures have created conditions necessary for dialogue
with Kosovo Albanian leaders, the assembly said, adding it has
fully met the requirements under the U.N. Security Council
resolution on the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
The assembly supported the Federal government's stand on the
Kosovo issue and called on the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) to make a fact-finding trip to the
troubled Serbian province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
