<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Implements Agri-Rehabilitation Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
been implementing agricultural rehabilitation programs in phases
providing support to 1 million families of poor, landless and
marginal farmers in the districts severely-affected by the recent
floods.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural rehabilitation programs involving 346.4
million taka (about 7.37 million U.S. dollars) will continue up to
December, and more programs in the form of development projects
are in the offing, The Independent daily Tuesday quoted official
sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
Under the first phase, the Department of Agricultural Extension
had distributed 52 tons of rice seeds free of charge among the
affected farmers. The Agriculture Ministry has also taken up the
first rehabilitation program to produce rice seedlings in
government farms for free distribution among the farmers.
</P>
<P>
The second rehabilitation program, at a cost of 81.2 million
taka (about 1.73 million dollars) was initiated in August to
support the farmers by providing them with seeds, fertilizer and
some cash.
</P>
<P>
In view of the huge damage caused by the flood, the government
has come forward with the third rehabilitation program involving
121.9 million taka (about 2.6 million dollars), under which, the
Agriculture Ministry has started distributing cash to the farmers
for procuring fertilizer, equipment and seeds for winter crops
like wheat, maize, pulses and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
The fourth program involving 142.5 million taka (about 3.03
million dollars) would start soon to extend support to more
deserving farmers in the affected districts.
</P>
<P>
Besides, a number of development projects involving 3.12
billion taka (about 66.4 million dollars) have also been planned
for the agricultural sector to produce more food.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, international organizations and bilateral donors
have come forward with assistance to the tune of 100 million taka
( 2.13 million dollars) for agricultural rehabilitation in the
affected areas.
</P>
<P>
The 10-week-long floods had destroyed crops on 580,000 hectares
of land in the country's 52 severely-affected districts, causing a
loss of about 40 billion taka (about 851.1 million dollars), while
farmers lost 3.5 million tons of crops including 2 million tons of
rice, according to the Department of Agricultural Extension.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
