<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Re-Elected Cardoso to Face up to Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President
Fernando Cardoso has won re-election according to initial results
received Monday, and it is anticipated he will have to deal with
more challenges in the second term to battle the nation's
worsening economy.
</P>
<P>
With 51.47 percent of the ballots counted, the 67-year-old
president garnered more votes than all his rivals together,
winning the election without requiring a second round.
</P>
<P>
Brazilians went to the polls on Sunday to elect their
President, governor, legislators, and state legislators. A total
of 27 state governorships, all the 513 seats in the lower house of
Congress, and one third of the seats in the Senate (27), and all
27 seats in the state assemblies were disputed.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso's second four-year term, which will start on January 1,
1999, is going to have a clear "human focus," the president's
advisors said, adding there will be ambitious projects to boost
the country's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso promised to invest 110 billion U.S. dollars in the
construction of harbors and telecommunication infrastructure so as
to create favorable conditions for foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
As for exports, the re-elected president plans to seek an
increase from the current level of 52.9 billion dollars to 100
billion by the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
He guaranteed that he would wipe out the current 7.8 percent
unemployment, which is affecting 5.7 million Brazilians out of the
economically active population of 70.3 million.
</P>
<P>
Also under reform plans are social health and education
systems. Cardoso will enlarge the health system to cover 80
million people, and the new education system will benefit 2.7
million youths and guarantee elementary schooling for 98 percent
of all the children in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The president has promised to create 20,000 new "Family Health"
centers to benefit 80 million people, and to invest one million
dollars in hospital infrastructure every year.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's homeless population of five million is another big
problem. Cardoso has announced a supporting plan which aims to
help 83.3 percent of the 30 million people living in extreme
poverty.
</P>
<P>
However, Cardoso's administration will have to provide
rigorous adjustment measures to congress to arrange public
accounts. Investors are pulling their money out of the world's
ninth largest economy, fearing the government will not obtain
financing for its huge budget deficit of nearly 60 billion
dollars, more than 7 percent of the gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's hard currency reserves, once a cushion against
speculation, plunged from 74 billion dollars in April to 45
billion dollars last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain, China Should Work Closely Together: Blair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 6 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair, who arrived in Beijing on Tuesday for a five-day official
visit, said that Britain and China should "work closely and
effectively together."
</P>
<P>
In an article written specially for China's People's Daily,
Blair noted that he is going to Beijing at a time when relations
between the two countries "have never been better."
</P>
<P>
The People's Daily Tuesday carried translated excerpts of the
article.
</P>
<P>
He said that Hong Kong's successful transition has opened the
door to a new partnership between Britain and China and that "the
pessimists have been proved wrong" as Hong Kong continues to be
one of the world's leading commercial and financial centers.
</P>
<P>
Citing trade ties as the base for Britain's strongest bilateral
relations, he said the two countries are "already cooperating more
closely, on more issues, than ever before."
</P>
<P>
British trade with China increased by 15 percent in 1997 and
Britain is Europe's leading investor in China, he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to a group of senior British business executives in
his delegation, Blair said they "personify the rapidly expanding
commercial relationship" between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He also mentioned other aspects of the bilateral relations,
including growing cultural links and new partnership in sport.
</P>
<P>
The British prime minister listed several appeals his country
holds, ranging from its commercial advantages to London's flair
for the cosmopolitan.
</P>
<P>
He said he wanted to build a "modern relationship" with China
and to consolidate a partnership which "looks forward, not back."
</P>
<P>
On the Hong Kong issue, he said that the "one country, two
systems" concept is now a reality and that Hong Kong has become a
"bridge" between the countries rather than a barrier that divides
them.
</P>
<P>
In his capacity of chairman of the Group of Eight Western
countries, Blair expressed welcome for Chinese Premier Zhu
Rongji's advice on handling the global financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
He lauded China's "responsible and coherent economic policies,
particularly regarding its determination not to devalue the
Renminbi," China's currency.
</P>
<P>
Describing China as "one of the great economies of the 21st
century," Blair said it will increasingly be called upon to share
the responsibilities of international leadership.
</P>
<P>
He urged cooperation on a wide range of issues: from terrorism
to nuclear proliferation; from international crime to global
poverty; from climate change to drugs.
</P>
<P>
Blair also acknowledged "very different backgrounds and
traditions" of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He wrote of the need to discuss the human rights issue, noting
that "persuasion and dialogue achieve more than confrontation and
empty rhetoric."
</P>
<P>
He cited the peace process in Northern Ireland as an example to
prove that "there are no differences so great that they cannot be
overcome."
</P>
<P>
The British prime minister called on the two countries to
tackle the challenges of the present together in order to forge a
new partnership for the future.
</P>
<P>
He expressed optimism that, with China's support, the
international community can face the challenges of globalization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
