<HEADLINE> Mexican Internet Users to Double by 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Mexico will have two million
Internet users by the end of 1999, coupled with a growth in
electronic commerce and a great potential need for
Internet-related professionals.
</P>
<P>
Given the fact that one million people are connected to the
Internet in Mexico now, the number will grow five-fold by the year
2003, said Eduardo Adame Goddard, chief executive officer (CEO) of
the Tecnofin company, citing market studies.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the state news agency Notimex, Adame said
that there is "an enormous potential" for Internet expansion and
there will be a great need for highly qualified professionals.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that trade through the Internet will result in a
change in labor structure. For instance, he noted, stores
connected with the Internet need less sellers and more stage coach
services.
</P>
<P>
He said that currently there are some 300 companies in Mexico
that have links or promotion programs with the Internet, and new
web sites offering products and services appear everyday.
</P>
<P>
He said, however, that the number of jobs created by the
Internet is still unknown.
</P>
<P>
With the dynamic expansion of the Internet, Adame said that
there will be readjustments in labor market soon just as in other
sectors around the world.
</P>
<P>
Mexican entrepreneurs will face major challenges because
foreign products are advertised through the Internet, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
