<HEADLINE> U.S. House Panel Votes to Open Clinton Impeachment Inquiry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Judiciary Committee of
the U.S. House of Representatives Monday approved opening an
impeachment inquiry into President Bill Clinton stemming from his
affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
The inquiry, approved on a 21-16 party-line vote, would be the
third in U.S. history and the first since President Richard
Nixon's Watergate scandal in 1974.
</P>
<P>
The full 435-member House has yet to approve the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
The resolution approved by the Judiciary Committee would allow
a broad, open-ended investigation of Clinton that could be
expanded to include Whitewater land deal, campaign fund-raising
abuses and other issues.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday Republicans had rejected a Democratic proposal
to limit the length and scope of the inquiry, confining the probe
to the Lewinsky matter and concluding it by late November.
</P>
<P>
A vote by the full House is expected later this week, before
Congress adjourns for the year and members scatter to campaign for
the November 3 mid-term elections.
</P>
<P>
During the Judiciary Committee debate earlier Monday, the
Republicans' top investigator alleged 15 potential impeachable
offenses by Clinton, four more than independent counsel Kenneth
Starr had cited in his report to Congress last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Traditional Export Earnings on Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's traditional
export earnings dropped 11 percent in the first eight months over
a year earlier despite a 13.3 percent growth in export tonnage.
</P>
<P>
The National Statistics Management Department on Monday
attributed the drop in export earnings to falling prices for the
main traditional products except coffee in the world market.
</P>
<P>
During the period, the department said, oil shipments rose by
21.7 percent, ferro-nickel by 12 percent and coal by 7.2
percent. But all of them suffered a substantial drop in prices.
</P>
<P>
Non-traditional exports, except gold and emeralds, posted a 4.3
percent rise during the same period.
</P>
<P>
The United States, the European Union and the Andean Community
accounted for 79.5 percent of Colombia's total exports in the
period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
