<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Minister Criticized for Denial of Rapes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
again come under fire as Minister of Defense and Security Wiranto
denied that scores of women were raped during the mid-May riots in
the country, the Jakarta Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of a government-sponsored fact-finding team
investigating the riots, Marzuki Darusman, on Monday slammed the
latest denial as "premature."
</P>
<P>
It was also a "shock," he said, given an earlier consensus that
officials would no longer issue such statements ahead of the
team's October 23 report deadline.
</P>
<P>
Marzuki was asked to comment on Wiranto's statement during a
news conference on the Armed Forces (ABRI)'s 53rd anniversary on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Wiranto, who is also commander of the Armed Forces, had said,
"The government and ABRI have made various efforts to find the
victims of the rapes reported to have taken place during the May
13 to May 15 unrest. These efforts have not yielded results. ABRI
has also not obtained concrete and convincing replies, data or
proof from parties that have claimed to possess important
information."
</P>
<P>
Wiranto made a similar statement in September along with other
senior officials, including the national police chief and the head
of the state intelligence agency, to the protest of human rights
groups.
</P>
<P>
Marzuki reiterated that a preliminary report, including data on
the rape cases, had been given to ABRI two weeks ago. There was a
consensus that sexual violence had occurred during the May riots
and that the government would no longer issue denials.
</P>
<P>
He said the denial may have been made because the ABRI
leadership might have felt frustrated for failing to successfully
reach out to victims, mostly Chinese-Indonesians, to verify
reported cases. But this should not have led them to conclude that
no rapes had taken place.
</P>
<P>
"I want to emphasize again that the rapes did occur. Now we are
investigating their magnitude," Marzuki said.
</P>
<P>
The government established the Joint Fact-Finding Team in July
to investigate reports that the May 13-15 riots were masterminded.
More than 1,200 people were killed and thousands of buildings and
vehicles damaged during the riots in Jakarta and other cities.
</P>
<P>
Activists have reported that 168 women were gang-raped or
otherwise sexually assaulted during the riots and 20 of them died
or committed suicide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
