<HEADLINE> U.S. to Dismantle Howard Air Base in Panama in Early 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States will start
dismantling Howard Air Base in Panama in 1999, Panamanian Foreign
Minister Jorge Ritter said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ritter said U.S. Army authorities informed him of the decision
after both countries announced on September 24 the failure of
their negotiations to create a multilateral anti-drug center at
the base, which is located three kilometers southwest of the
Panamanian city.
</P>
<P>
Howard Air Base could have been used to control drug
trafficking by tracking airplanes and boats carrying drugs from
South America to the U.S., according to negotiations between the
two countries that started in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The new Panamanian government will come into office in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Howard Air Base occupies 1,735 hectares, with 609 buildings and
a 2,485-meter runway. 
</P>
