<HEADLINE> Indonesian Economy to Contract This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's economy is expected
to contract by 13.7 percent in 1998 against a rise of 4.6 percent
in 1997, the Indonesian Observer Tuesday quoted the Central Bureau
of Statistics as saying.
</P>
<P>
The prediction is higher than the government's earlier estimate
of 12.23 percent, but lower than the International Monetary Fund's
figure of 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Central Bureau of Statistics Sugito Suwito said
the country's gross domestic product (GDP) shrank 13.59 percent in
the nine months to September as compared to the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
"GDP has contracted by 13.59 percent until September. For the
full year, GDP is likely to contract by 13.7 percent," he said.
</P>
<P>
On trade, Sugito said the country booked a trade surplus of
2.15 billion U.S. dollars in July, down from 2.38 billion dollars
in June.
</P>
<P>
In the January-July period, exports totaled 29.225 billion
dollars, a 2.89-percent drop from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
In the seven month period, imports totaled 15.75 billion U.S.
dollars, representing a fall of 37.13 percent against the year-ago
period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Cancels All Preseason Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The NBA league announced
Monday that it had to cancel the total of 90 entire preseason
exhibition games because of stalled labor negotiations with the
players.
</P>
<P>
"At this point, our teams cannot possibly be ready to play any
games before November," deputy commissioner Russ Granik said.
"It's sad that we have been unable to have any meaningful
negotiations."
</P>
<P>
The both sides will meet Thursday for the second formal
collective bargaining session. The league threatened it would
make decisions concerning possible cancellation of regular season
games next week. The regular season set to start on November 3.
</P>
<P>
Even if a new agreement is reached this week, it will take at
least three weeks to sign players, make trades and hold
abbreviated training camps. So unless a deal can be completed a
few days after the sides reconvene, there appears to be no way
the season can start on time.
</P>
<P>
The owners offered a new proposal 10 days ago to the players.
But the players union said the core issue of the dispute remained
unchanged in the 16-page proposal.
</P>
<P>
"Our proposals would result in an average player salary of
more than 3.1 million dollars and a minimum salary for 10-year
veterans of 50,000 dollars," said Granik Monday. "Unfortunately,
the union leadership has been unwilling to give any serious
consideration to what we have offered."
</P>
<P>
The union plans to send players to about a dozen arenas
tomorrow to try to gain public support for their position.
</P>
<P>
Both sides are waiting a ruling from arbitrator John Feerick
on the union's grievance over whether players with guaranteed
contracts should be paid during the lockout. Feerick's decision
could come at any time before October 19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
