<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chain Store Giant in China's Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Seven years ago, the people of
Shanghai didn't think much of the future of chain stores and
several went bankrupt in a very short period of time. But all that
has changed.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai now has about 1,000 of them, and the Lianhua
Supermarket Corporation was a pioneer. It is a giant in the chain
store business, one that changed the fate of chain stores.
</P>
<P>
Lianhua was set up by the Shanghai Trade Corporation in May
1991, and succeeded with the first chain store in the Quyang
Residential District, mainly by providing daily use items.
</P>
<P>
By 1994, it had a dozen shops. It did encounter a few problems
but refused to give up, and instead improved management by
introducing computers and expanding the range of goods from
daily-use articles to fresh food and better vegetables.
</P>
<P>
It also set up 13 joint ventures and opened a large supermarket
with the French company Carrefour.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, Lianhua's capital had grown from 1.2
million yuan to 190 million yuan, with its sales revenue reaching
2.4 billion yuan that year.
</P>
<P>
It now has stores in more than 30 cities in neighboring
Jiangsu, Zhejiang and Anhui provinces.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
