<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for Strengthened Financial Architecture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
on Monday called for a strengthened worldwide financial structure
to handle emerging financial troubles and prevent global recession.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting here with world financial officials,
Clinton pledged that the United States would contribute money to
help replenish the International Monetary Fund's (IMF) coffers.
He also urged Japan to move quickly to address the current global
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Every leading industrial economy has a role to play, including
the United States, by providing full support for IMF funding,
while Japan can also help by moving quickly to address its
economic and financial challenges," Clinton said at the start of a
Group of 22 meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Group includes the Group of Seven (G-7) leading industrial
nations as well as key emerging market countries and regions.
There were originally 22 economies in the group, but four more
joined this year.
</P>
<P>
The Monday evening meeting, attended by finance ministers and
central bank governors and other high-level financial officials,
was convened by U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan. It coincided with the IMF-World
Bank annual meeting in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Discussions were held among the G-7 and IMF Interim Committee
and other world financial bodies during the weekend, focusing on
the worsening financial turmoil in Asia, Russia and Latin
America. There was little progress in formulating major steps to
end the crisis.
</P>
<P>
For the U.S., the Clinton administration has to work hard to
win from the Republican-dominated Congress an approval for 18
billion U.S. dollars in money for the IMF.
</P>
<P>
"We must ensure that the international financial architecture
is prepared for the new challenges of our time, especially the
challenge of building a system that will lessen and manage the
risks in the global market to allow countries to reap the benefits
of free flowing capital in a way that is safe and sustainable,"
Clinton told the officials.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president is also scheduled to address the opening
session of the IMF-World Bank meetings on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
