<HEADLINE> Sweden Supports Debt Relief for Poorest Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Sweden plans to support a
special initiative of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and
the World Bank to make debt relief available to the poorest
countries in the world, the Swedish Foreign Ministry said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The decision, announced at the annual meeting of the IMF and
the World Bank now underway in Washington, means that Sweden will
make a second contribution amounting to 125 million Swedish kronor
(15.7 million U.S. dollars) to the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries
(HIPC) Debt Initiative.
</P>
<P>
In July this year, Sweden decided to set aside 445 million
Swedish kronor (55.9 million dollars) for debt relief and budget
support in seven poor and heavily indebted countries -- Bolivia,
Cape Verde, Mozambique, Nicaragua, Tanzania, Uganda and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 40 of the world's poorest countries may be
considered for the debt relief under the HIPC initiative, which
was launched two years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
