<HEADLINE> Security Council Urges Iraq to Resume Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations Monday urged Iraq to respond quickly to its
call and resume cooperation with the United Nations arms
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the council was briefed by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan on his recent contacts with Iraq's
Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Annan held two rounds of talks with Aziz last week. But no
results were yielded. The third round of talks between them will
take place Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Aziz has been here for a week, during which time he consulted
with Annan and members of the Security Council on what a new
comprehensive review of Iraq's relations with the United Nations
would contain. Aziz is not expected to make a decision on whether
to rescind Iraq's ban on most U.N. arms inspections until he
leaves New York and speaks to Iraq's President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Iraq announced suspension of cooperation with the United
Nations arms inspectors in early August. Security Council decided
to suspend its regular review on U.N. sanctions against Iraq until
it resumes cooperation with the United Nations. The council
offered a comprehensive review of Iraq's compliance with U.N.
relevant resolutions once it resumes cooperation. 
</P>
