<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Panel Defeats Democrats' Alternative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Republicans on the U.S.House
of Representatives Judiciary Committee Monday voted down a
Democratic attempt to limit the time and scope of any impeachment
inquiry of President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The committee on a party-line vote of 21-16 rejected the
Democratic effort and moved toward passage of a Republican
proposal for a wide-ranging, open-ended impeachment inquiry into
the president's actions.
</P>
<P>
The Democrats' alternative would have limited the scope of the
impeachment inquiry only to any wrongdoings Clinton may have
committed in his affair with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
It also asked for early hearings on what would be standards for
impeachment. It called for a timetable whereby the committee would
complete its impeachment work by November 17 and the entire House
would vote by November 25.
</P>
<P>
But Republicans argued such restrictions would be an invitation
for delay and said there was no precedent for them in previous
impeachment inquiries.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic alternative was the first vote in a day-long
hearing looking into the first possible presidential impeachment
inquiry since Watergate in 1974. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank-IMF Joint Committee Endorses Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Development Committee of
the World Bank and the IMF Monday agreed on a concerted strategy
for restoring sustainable growth and reversing the dramatic
increase in poverty in the crisis-stricken East Asia.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued following the 58th meeting of the joint
committee of the two world financial institutions highlighted some
key elements of the strategy which includes maintenance and
acceleration of progress on structural reforms, including
governance structures required for the efficient working of
markets and restructuring of the banking system and corporate
sectors and, in the short term, restoration of credit to viable
businesses.
</P>
<P>
The strategy also includes mobilization of necessary resources
to finance growth, regeneration of demand as well as protection of
the environment.
</P>
<P>
"Crucial to all these elements is a focus on social concerns
and the need to mitigate the most harmful effects of the crisis on
the poor," the document stressed.
</P>
<P>
The ministers attending the meeting recognized that the
economic and social aftershocks of the crisis were "more severe
than earlier anticipated." The crisis had now "spread beyond
Indonesia, (South) Korea, Thailand and Malaysia, and its global
ramifications had increased the vulnerability of all countries,"
the communique noted.
</P>
<P>
If the situation was allowed to continued, "financial turmoil
could result in major setbacks to the global economy, and
particularly to the progress most developing countries had
achieved in the 1990," the ministers warned.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the committee agreed that actions were needed to
help restore confidence and prevent contagion in the event of
market pressure. Emerging market countries should strengthen their
policies and institutions at an early stage to minimize their
vulnerability to adverse shifts in investment sentiment.
Meanwhile, industrial countries should take early and decisive
actions to help regain or maintain growth momentum and global
financial stability. "All countries should continue the process of
market opening and resist protectionism. All countries and the
international financial institutions need to attach high priority
to the promotion of good governance and the elimination of
corruption," the communique underlined.
</P>
<P>
The ministers were encouraged by the progress made in carrying
out the Debt Initiative for Heavily Indebted Poor Countries during
the initiative's first two years. It was noted that nine countries
have so far reached the decision point, and total commitments to
the seven requiring assistance under the initiative amount to some
6.1 billion U.S. dollars in nominal debt service relief, or 3.1
billion dollars in net present value terms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
