<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Voters Start Registration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Nigerians throughout the country
started registering as voters Monday for elections that will end
military rule in the most populous African nation in May next
year.
</P>
<P>
In registration centers visited by our reporter in Lagos,
Nigeria's commercial center and largest city, no long queues were
sighted but people keep coming to register for the elections.
</P>
<P>
An automobile mechanic, however, said he will not register
because he is not interested in the vote.
</P>
<P>
The Independent Electoral Commission (INEC) has advertized on
major national media, urging people to register and support "this
patriotic task."
</P>
<P>
"This is golden opportunity for all of us to realize our long
cherished yearning for democratic governance," the advertizement
said.
</P>
<P>
The INEC has increased the number of registration centers and
polling stations from 75,000 in the last exercise to 111,430 this
time.
</P>
<P>
It will also create more electoral wards to bring ballot boxes
closer to voters.
</P>
<P>
The exercise will take two weeks.
</P>
<P>
About 56 million people out of Nigeria's 104 million
population were registered as voters during the transition to
civil rule program of late military leader General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
Abacha was set to transform himself into a civilian president
in a election with himself as the sole candidate of the four
political parties registered by his government, before he died of
heart disease suddenly in June.
</P>
<P>
General Abdulsalam Abubakar, former Chief of Defense Staff was
chosen by the armed forces to lead the West African country.
</P>
<P>
Since June when he took office, Abubakar has taken bold
measures in both political and economic fronts that won him
backing by Nigerians and Western nations, who have offered to
ease and lift sanctions imposed on Nigeria during the Abacha
time.
</P>
<P>
In his efforts of national reconciliation, he had freed all
political detainees and held wide dialog with opposition groups
as well as exiled dissidents.
</P>
<P>
He also announced massive privatization program in an effort
to revitalize Nigeria's ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
And most of all, he scrapped Abacha's discredited transition
program, including the parties registered by the former leader.
</P>
<P>
He announced a new transition program that will return Nigeria
to civilian rule by May 29, 1999. He declared publicly that he
will not contend and will retire from the armed forces at the end
of transition program.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has witnessed eight military leaders since
independence from British rule in 1960, with only two civilian
presidents.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's last successful presidential election was held in
1979. The election on June 12, 1993 was deemed to be free and
fair but was annulled by the then military leader of General
Ibrahim Babangida. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Habitat Day Marked with Focus on Safer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 5 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan called Monday, the World Habitat Day, for international
efforts against urban crimes to build up safer cities.
</P>
<P>
"Urban violence around the world is estimated to have nearly
doubled in the last 20 years," Annan said in a message issued by
the Nairobi-based U.N. Center for Human Settlements (Habitat).
</P>
<P>
"Cities do seem to be breeding grounds for a wide range of
lawless acts," Annan said, citing unemployment, easy availability
of guns, worsening urban environments, the huge gap between the
rich and the poor and a breakdown of traditional value systems as
among major factors behind the rampant city crimes.
</P>
<P>
"I urge all (U.N.) member states, local governments and
citizens of cities around the world to mark Habitat Day his year
by taking action to make their cities and communities safer and
better places to live in," Annan said in his message.
</P>
<P>
Habitat chief Claus Topfer Monday urged local governments
worldwide to find ways to help communities tackle problems that
determine community safety and result in crime, according to a
report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
"Local governments have to promote personal security and
reduce fear by improving police services, making them more
accountable to the communities they serve, and by encouraging the
formation of community-based crime prevention measures and
systems," he was quoted as saying.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
