<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Teachers Start Strike, Clash with Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Tens of thousands of teachers
started strike Monday in confrontation with the police across
Kenya in a desperate bid to press the government to implement its
pledges of teachers' pay rise.
</P>
<P>
The 250,000-strong Kenya National Union of Teachers (KNUT),
which called the strike -- their third in a year, said that all
its 5,000 members in the capital participated in the strike
today.
</P>
<P>
"So far the strike has been very successful... The schools are
not operating," said Mureu Kamau, chief of KNUT's Nairobi branch.
</P>
<P>
Anti-riot police quelled a demonstration of some 1,000
teachers taking to streets in downtown Nairobi on the day. At
least five people were said to have been detained.
</P>
<P>
College students also protested in support of the teachers.
Some 500 students blocked a main road 30 kilometers west of
Nairobi with fires, stoning passing motorists and the police. The
latter responded with tear-gas and rubber bullets.
</P>
<P>
In Migori District, southwestern Kenya, scores of teachers
were injured and one policeman was badly beaten in violent
clashes, Kenya News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The strike by teachers at public schools also affected the
operation of private schools. Sources told Xinhua that more than
half of the pupils were absent at Nairobi's private schools which
had canceled all scheduled extra curricula due to the strike.
</P>
<P>
Striking teachers demonstrated outside private schools,
causing disturbances among the pupils there. Local analysts
predicted that the situation will be tenser in the coming couple
of days.
</P>
<P>
In the Braeburn Primary School, one of the leading private
schools in Nairobi, the teachers have asked parents to take their
children in and out of school themselves instead of using school
commuters.
</P>
<P>
Labor Minister Joseph Ngutu charged in a statement Monday that
the striking teachers were in breach of a no-strike agreement,
warning that they "must take full responsibility for their
actions."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Assistant Minister in the Office of the President
Simon Kiptum Choge also warned that all striking teachers will be
sacked.
</P>
<P>
"If teachers insist on taking the government head-on, they
will end up the losers," he said.
</P>
<P>
In response, KNUT officials vowed to "stay on strike" until
the government carry out the second phase of a 150-200 pay rise
deal it agreed on in July last year.
</P>
<P>
At least 21 opposition members of parliament have openly
supported the strike.
</P>
<P>
Teachers' salaries range from 2,700 Shillings to 29,000
Shillings (45 to 480 U.S. Dollars) a month, relatively higher
than most other civil servants in this east African country. The
government said the economy at present cannot afford to meet the
demands of the teachers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
