<DOCNO> XIE19981006.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Market Stable, Trading Well: Financial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong market is now
stable and trading well thanks to a "surgical incursion" for 10
trading days in August, a senior official from the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (KHSAR) of China said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Donald Tsang, KHSAR financial secretary who is here attending
the annual meeting of the World Bank and International Monetary
Fund (IMF), told a press conference that the exceptional incursion
was introduced to remove a "contrived, artificial and manufactured
situation" which was causing major disruption and threatening to
undermine the confidence of the people.
</P>
<P>
To dispel foreign doubts about the move, Tsang said that the
measures are "totally transparent and rule-based" and not at all
amounting to capital control.
</P>
<P>
The secretary has met with several finance ministers and other
officials here since his arrival last Saturday. Their talks
focused on greater transparency and disclosure of interests in
Market activities and discipline on monitoring international fund
flows.
</P>
<P>
"I believe we are in a very crucial juncture in economic
evolution of modern history," Tsang said, citing as a proof the
fall of four major currencies in Asia, the continuous instability
in Russia, the critical lack of activity and sense of rapid
recovery in the Japanese economy, the major correction in the Wall
Street and the potential serious problems emerging in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
"It is no exaggeration that if these problems are not quickly
addressed, and addressed properly, we are facing up to a global
recession," the official warned.
</P>
<P>
He called for due attention to the negative impact of
exceedingly large-sized capital flow and for efforts to stem
irregularity in the banking sector in particular.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the goal, Tsang added, it is necessary to enhance
transparency and disclosure of activities as well as supervision.
He urged the world countries to work together to address the
problems in Japan, Russia and Brazil without further delay.
</P>
<P>
He spoke highly of China's determination to keep its currency
renminbi strong. "The renminbi, as I say, is a very strong
currency... there is a firm political commitment from the
leadership of China that the currency should not be devalued."
</P>
<P>
Secretary Tsang is on a three-week mission to Europe and the
United States designed to exchange views with other financial
leaders on the restoration of order and stability in the
international financial markets.
</P>
<P>
The trip has taken Tsang to Frankfurt, Munich, the Hague and
Amsterdam, and will lead him to Now York, Boston, London and
Edinburgh. He planned to deliver about 10 keynote speeches during
his visit.
</P>
<P>
Tsang said he wished to be able to gather first-hand knowledge
on the development of the Euro dollar and its implications for
Hong Kong, while trying to dispel any misunderstanding or doubts
about Hong Kong's recent counter-activities in the stock and
futures markets.
</P>
<P>
"I am glad to say that misunderstanding has now been largely
removed, from what I have discussed with people in Europe and here
over the last 10 days about what Hong Kong has done," Tsang told
reporters at the press conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
