<HEADLINE> Boeing Delivers Fewer Jets in Third Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Boeing delivered 123
commercial jets in the third quarter ending September 30, a 10
percent decline from the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
The company said in a report that at the end of the quarter
there were 36 undelivered commercial airplanes in storage, waiting
for customer-financing arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Boeing delivered 137 jets in the second quarter and had hoped
to deliver more in the third quarter. The reduced deliveries will
cut into Boeing's third-quarter profit and put a lot of pressure
on the company in the last quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the company delivered 89 jets in the third quarter
as production problems delayed their completion. Those problems,
which plagued the company for more than a year, now are abating
after costing Boeing nearly two billion U.S. dollars. Last month
the company ousted the chief of its commercial airplane operation.
</P>
<P>
The third-quarter shortfall is believed to reflect financial
problems Asian carriers are now having. Only last week Thailand
ordered Thai Airways to cancel orders for two 777s and delay
deliveries of other planes.
</P>
<P>
Another factor, according to Seattle Times, is the lack of
available financial aid from the U.S. Export-Import Bank. Several
purchasers, including Turkish Airlines, have sought aid from the
bank, which is awaiting federal funding as the new fiscal year
gets under way this month.
</P>
<P>
Boeing plans to deliver 550 commercial jet this year. The
third-quarter deliveries bring the total in the first nine months
to 370, leaving 123 deliveries if the company is to meet its goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
